# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: amoeboid-movement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-binding-protein] Many actin-binding proteins, including α-actinin, β-spectrin, dystrophin, utrophin and fimbrin, do this through the actin-binding calponin homology domain.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-binding-protein] This is a list of **actin-binding proteins** in alphabetical order.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Actin was first discovered in rabbit skeletal muscle in the mid 1940s by F.B.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Huxley demonstrated that actin is essential for muscle contraction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The mechanism in which actin creates long filaments was first described in the mid 1980s.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Later studies showed that actin has an important role in cell shape, motility, and cytokinesis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Actin filaments are assembled in two general types of structures: bundles and networks.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Bundles can be composed of polar filament arrays, in which all barbed ends point to the same end of the bundle, or non-polar arrays, where the barbed ends point towards both ends.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] A class of actin-binding proteins, called cross-linking proteins, dictate the formation of these structures.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Cross-linking proteins determine filament orientation and spacing in the bundles and networks.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] These structures are regulated by many other classes of actin-binding proteins, including motor proteins, branching proteins, severing proteins, polymerization promoters, and capping proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Measuring approximately 7 nm in diameter, microfilaments are the thinnest fibers of the cytoskeleton.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] They are polymers of actin subunits (globular actin, or G-actin), which as part of the fiber are referred to as filamentous actin, or F-actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Each microfilament is made up of two helical, interlaced strands of subunits.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Much like microtubules, actin filaments are polarized.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Electron micrographs have provided evidence of their fast-growing barbed-ends and their slow-growing pointed-end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] This polarity has been determined by the pattern created by the binding of myosin S1 fragments: they themselves are subunits of the larger myosin II protein complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The pointed end is commonly referred to as the minus (−) end and the barbed end is referred to as the plus (+) end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Subsequently, ADP-actin dissociates slowly from the pointed end, a process significantly accelerated by the actin-binding protein, cofilin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] ADP bound cofilin severs ADP-rich regions nearest the (−)-ends.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Upon release, the free actin monomer slowly dissociates from ADP, which in turn rapidly binds to the free ATP diffusing in the cytosol, thereby forming the ATP-actin monomeric units needed for further barbed-end filament elongation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] This rapid turnover is important for the cell's movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] End-capping proteins such as CapZ prevent the addition or loss of monomers at the filament end where actin turnover is unfavorable, such as in the muscle apparatus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Actin polymerization together with capping proteins were recently used to control the 3-dimensional growth of protein filament so as to perform 3D topologies useful in technology and the making of electrical interconnect.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Electrical conductivity is obtained by metallisation of the protein 3D structure.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] As a result of ATP hydrolysis, filaments elongate approximately 10 times faster at their barbed ends than their pointed ends.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] At steady-state, the polymerization rate at the barbed end matches the depolymerization rate at the pointed end, and microfilaments are said to be treadmilling.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Treadmilling results in elongation in the barbed end and shortening in the pointed-end, so that the filament in total moves.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Since both processes are energetically favorable, this means force is generated, the energy ultimately coming from ATP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Intracellular actin cytoskeletal assembly and disassembly are tightly regulated by cell signaling mechanisms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Many signal transduction systems use the actin cytoskeleton as a scaffold, holding them at or near the inner face of the peripheral membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] This subcellular location allows immediate responsiveness to transmembrane receptor action and the resulting cascade of signal-processing enzymes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] In most animal cells, monomeric actin is bound to profilin and thymosin beta-4, both of which preferentially bind with one-to-one stoichiometry to ATP-containing monomers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Although thymosin beta-4 is strictly a monomer-sequestering protein, the behavior of profilin is far more complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Profilin enhances the ability of monomers to assemble by stimulating the exchange of actin-bound ADP for solution-phase ATP to yield actin-ATP and ADP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Profilin is transferred to the leading edge by virtue of its PIP2 binding site, and it employs its poly-L-proline binding site to dock onto end-tracking proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Once bound, profilin-actin-ATP is loaded into the monomer-insertion site of actoclampin motors.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Specialized unique actin cytoskeletal structures are found adjacent to the plasma membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Four remarkable examples include red blood cells, human embryonic kidney cells, neurons, and sperm cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] In red blood cells, a spectrin-actin hexagonal lattice is formed by interconnected short actin filaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] In human embryonic kidney cells, the cortical actin forms a scale-free fractal structure.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] And in mammalian sperm, actin forms a helical structure in the midpiece, i.e., the first segment of the flagellum.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] In non-muscle cells, actin filaments are formed close to membrane surfaces.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The actin filament network in non-muscle cells is highly dynamic.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The actin filament network is arranged with the barbed-end of each filament attached to the cell's peripheral membrane by means of clamped-filament elongation motors, the above-mentioned "actoclampins", formed from a filament barbed-end and a clamping protein (formins, VASP, Mena, WASP, and N-WASP).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The primary substrate for these elongation motors is profilin-actin-ATP complex which is directly transferred to elongating filament ends.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The pointed-end of each filament is oriented toward the cell's interior.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] In the case of lamellipodial growth, the Arp2/3 complex generates a branched network, and in filopodia a parallel array of filaments is formed.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Myosin motors are intracellular ATP-dependent enzymes that bind to and move along actin filaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Various classes of myosin motors have very different behaviors, including exerting tension in the cell and transporting cargo vesicles.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] One proposed model suggests the existence of actin filament barbed-end-tracking molecular motors termed "actoclampins".
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The proposed actoclampins generate the propulsive forces needed for actin-based motility of lamellipodia, filopodia, invadipodia, dendritic spines, intracellular vesicles, and motile processes in endocytosis, exocytosis, podosome formation, and phagocytosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Actoclampins also propel such intracellular pathogens as *Listeria monocytogenes*, *Shigella flexneri*, *Vaccinia* and *Rickettsia*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] When assembled under suitable conditions, these end-tracking molecular motors can also propel biomimetic particles.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] An actin filament end-tracking protein may thus be termed a *clampin*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Dickinson and Purich recognized that prompt ATP hydrolysis could explain the forces achieved during actin-based motility.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] They proposed a simple mechano-enzymatic sequence known as the *Lock, Load & Fire Model*, in which an end-tracking protein remains tightly bound (locked or clamped) onto the end of one sub-filament of the double-stranded actin filament.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] When operating with the benefit of ATP hydrolysis, AC motors generate per-filament forces of 8–9 pN, which is far greater than the per-filament limit of 1–2 pN for motors operating without ATP hydrolysis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The term actoclampin is generic and applies to all actin filament end-tracking molecular motors, irrespective of whether they are driven actively by an ATP-activated mechanism or passively.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Some actoclampins (e.g., those involving Ena/VASP proteins, WASP, and N-WASP) apparently require Arp2/3-mediated filament initiation to form the actin polymerization nucleus that is then "loaded" onto the end-tracker before processive motility can commence.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] To generate a new filament, Arp2/3 requires a "mother" filament, monomeric ATP-actin, and an activating domain from Listeria ActA or the VCA region of N-WASP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] The Arp2/3 complex binds to the side of the mother filament, forming a Y-shaped branch having a 70-degree angle with respect to the longitudinal axis of the mother filament.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Then upon activation by ActA or VCA, the Arp complex is believed to undergo a major conformational change, bringing its two actin-related protein subunits near enough to each other to generate a new filament gate.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-filaments] Whether ATP hydrolysis may be required for nucleation and/or Y-branch release is a matter under active investigation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] An actin protein is the monomeric subunit of two types of filaments in cells: microfilaments, one of the three major components of the cytoskeleton, and thin filaments, part of the contractile apparatus in muscle cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It can be present as either a free monomer called **G-actin** (globular) or as part of a linear polymer microfilament called **F-actin** (filamentous), both of which are essential for such important cellular functions as the mobility and contraction of cells during cell division.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin participates in many important cellular processes, including muscle contraction, cell motility, cell division and cytokinesis, vesicle and organelle movement, cell signaling, and the establishment and maintenance of cell junctions and cell shape.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Many of these processes are mediated by extensive and intimate interactions of actin with cellular membranes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In vertebrates, three main groups of actin isoforms, alpha, beta, and gamma have been identified.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The alpha actins, found in muscle tissues, are a major constituent of the contractile apparatus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The beta and gamma actins coexist in most cell types as components of the cytoskeleton, and as mediators of internal cell motility.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It is believed that the diverse range of structures formed by actin enabling it to fulfill such a large range of functions is regulated through the binding of tropomyosin along the filaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] A cell's ability to dynamically form microfilaments provides the scaffolding that allows it to rapidly remodel itself in response to its environment or to the organism's internal signals, for example, to increase cell membrane absorption or increase cell adhesion in order to form cell tissue.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Other enzymes or organelles such as cilia can be anchored to this scaffolding in order to control the deformation of the external cell membrane, which allows endocytosis and cytokinesis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It can also produce movement either by itself or with the help of molecular motors.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin therefore contributes to processes such as the intracellular transport of vesicles and organelles as well as muscular contraction and cellular migration.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It therefore plays an important role in embryogenesis, the healing of wounds, and the invasivity of cancer cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The evolutionary origin of actin can be traced to prokaryotic cells, which have equivalent proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin homologs from prokaryotes and archaea polymerize into different helical or linear filaments consisting of one or multiple strands.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] However the in-strand contacts and nucleotide binding sites are preserved in prokaryotes and in archaea.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Lastly, actin plays an important role in the control of gene expression.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] A large number of illnesses and diseases are caused by mutations in alleles of the genes that regulate the production of actin or of its associated proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The production of actin is also key to the process of infection by some pathogenic microorganisms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Mutations in the different genes that regulate actin production in humans can cause muscular diseases, variations in the size and function of the heart as well as deafness.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The make-up of the cytoskeleton is also related to the pathogenicity of intracellular bacteria and viruses, particularly in the processes related to evading the actions of the immune system.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin's primary role in the cell is to form linear polymers called microfilaments that serve various functions in the cell's structure, trafficking networks, migration, and replication.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The multifaceted role of actin relies on a few of the microfilaments' properties: First, the formation of actin filaments is reversible, and their function often involves undergoing rapid polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Second, microfilaments are polarized – i.e. the two ends of a filament are distinct from one another.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Third, actin filaments can bind to many other proteins, which together help modify and organize microfilaments for their diverse functions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin is extremely abundant in most cells, comprising 1–5% of the total protein mass of most cells, and 10% of muscle cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The actin protein is found in both the cytoplasm and the cell nucleus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Its location is regulated by cell membrane signal transduction pathways that integrate the stimuli that a cell receives stimulating the restructuring of the actin networks in response.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The role of actin as a regulator of chemical processes in the cell cytoplasm was proposed.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The cytoplasm is viscous, crowded, and heterogeneous, a dynamic complex, a gel-like substance that restricts free diffusion but is capable of managing a myriad of reactions at any moment.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The high capacity of the cytoplasm to perform complex chemical reactions can be explained by a two-phase system of organization, in which catalytic complexes are immobilized in the elastic solid phase (cytomatrix), thereby overcoming spatial hindrances and crowding .
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Nutrients and substrates can be delivered by liquid-phase (cytosol) flux, and the motor protein actin provides the driving force for cytomatrix mechanics.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Approximately 150 actin-binding and regulatory proteins fine-tune metabolic processes in the cytoplasm, thereby overcoming cytoplasmic viscosity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The energy source for actin dynamics in normal physiological conditions is mitochondria.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] However, cancer cells, due to their high metabolic rate, require additional ATP, which can be supplied by glycolysis (the Warburg effect).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] There are a number of different types of actin with slightly different structures and functions. α-actin is found exclusively in muscle fibres, while β- and γ-actin are found in other cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] As the latter types have a high turnover rate the majority of them are found outside permanent structures.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin's cytoskeleton is key to the processes of endocytosis, cytokinesis, determination of cell polarity and morphogenesis in yeasts.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In addition to relying on actin, these processes involve 20 or 30 associated proteins, which all have a high degree of evolutionary conservation, along with many signalling molecules.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Together these elements allow a spatially and temporally modulated assembly that defines a cell's response to both internal and external stimuli.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Yeasts contain three main elements that are associated with actin: patches, cables, and rings.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Despite not being present for long, these structures are subject to a dynamic equilibrium due to continual polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Plant genome studies have revealed the existence of protein isovariants within the actin family of genes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Within *Arabidopsis thaliana*, a model organism, there are ten types of actin, six profilins, and dozens of myosins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This diversity is explained by the evolutionary necessity of possessing variants that slightly differ in their temporal and spatial expression.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The majority of these proteins were jointly expressed in the tissue analysed.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin networks are distributed throughout the cytoplasm of cells that have been cultivated *in vitro*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] There is a concentration of the network around the nucleus that is connected via spokes to the cellular cortex, this network is highly dynamic, with a continuous polymerization and depolymerization.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Even though the majority of plant cells have a cell wall that defines their morphology, their microfilaments can generate sufficient force to achieve a number of cellular activities, such as the cytoplasmic currents generated by the microfilaments and myosin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in the movement of organelles and in cellular morphogenesis, which involve cell division as well as the elongation and differentiation of the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Nuclear actin was first noticed and described in 1977 by Clark and Merriam.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Authors describe a protein present in the nuclear fraction, obtained from *Xenopus laevis* oocytes, which shows the same features as skeletal muscle actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The actin sequence does not contain a nuclear localization signal.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The small size of actin (about 43 kDa) allows it to enter the nucleus by passive diffusion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The import of actin into the nucleus (probably in a complex with cofilin) is facilitated by the import protein importin 9.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Low levels of actin in the nucleus seems to be important, because actin has two nuclear export signals (NES) in its sequence.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Microinjected actin is quickly removed from the nucleus to the cytoplasm.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin is exported at least in two ways, through exportin 1 and exportin 6.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Specific modifications, such as SUMOylation, allows for nuclear actin retention.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] A mutation preventing SUMOylation causes rapid export of beta actin from the nucleus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Nuclear actin exists mainly as a monomer, but can also form dynamic oligomers and short polymers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Nuclear actin organization varies in different cell types.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] For example, in *Xenopus* oocytes (with higher nuclear actin level in comparison to somatic cells) actin forms filaments, which stabilize nucleus architecture.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These filaments can be observed under the microscope thanks to fluorophore-conjugated phalloidin staining.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In somatic cell nuclei, however, actin filaments cannot be observed using this technique.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The DNase I inhibition assay, the only test which allows the quantification of the polymerized actin directly in biological samples, has revealed that endogenous nuclear actin indeed occurs mainly in a monomeric form.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Precisely controlled level of actin in the cell nucleus, lower than in the cytoplasm, prevents the formation of filaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The polymerization is also reduced by the limited access to actin monomers, which are bound in complexes with ABPs, mainly cofilin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Different isoforms of actin are present in the cell nucleus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The level of actin isoforms may change in response to stimulation of cell growth or arrest of proliferation and transcriptional activity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Research on nuclear actin is focused on isoform beta.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] However the use of antibodies directed against different actin isoforms allows identifying not only the cytoplasmic beta in the cell nucleus, but also alpha- and gamma-actin in certain cell types.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The presence of different isoforms of actin may have a significant effect on its function in nuclear processes, as the level of individual isoforms can be controlled independently.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Functions of actin in the nucleus are associated with its ability to polymerize and interact with various ABPs and with structural elements of the nucleus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Due to its ability to undergo conformational changes and interaction with many proteins, actin acts as a regulator of formation and activity of protein complexes such as transcriptional complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin is also involved in cell movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Several different types of protrusions mediated directly or indirectly by actin are involved in cell migration in different ways, with the most important ones being lamellipodia, filopodia, invadopodia and blebs.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] A meshwork of actin filaments marks the forward edge of a moving cell, and the polymerization of new actin filaments pushes the cell membrane forward in protrusions called lamellipodia.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These membrane protrusions then attach to the substrate, forming structures known as focal adhesions that connect to the actin network.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Once attached, the rear of the cell body contracts squeezing its contents forward past the adhesion point.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Once the adhesion point has moved to the rear of the cell, the cell disassembles it, allowing the rear of the cell to move forward.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Filopodia are thin extensions of the plasma membrane that contain parallel bundles of actin filaments, in contrast to the branched actin structures of lamellipodia.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] They serve an exploratory role, being used by cells to probe their environment.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] While the presence of filopodia is linked to enhanced cell migration, they are not directly involved in cell body displacement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Invadopodia are actin-driven membrane protrusions that help to degrade the extracellular matrix.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] They are used by cancer cells for cell invasion, particularly to help them cross the basement membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The matrix degradation takes place by transporting vesicles containing matrix-degrading proteins to the invadopodia where the proteins are released via exocytosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Blebs are spherical membrane protrusions that are involved in both apoptosis and cell movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The driving force behind bleb extension is hydrostatic pressure, rather than actin filament elongation which drives lamellipodia, filopodia and invadopodia extension.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Blebs are formed by actomyosin contraction, which causes the delamination of the plasma membrane from the actin cortex or a focal rupture of the actin cortex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] They are then stabilized via actin cortex reassembly and finally retracted via actomyosin contraction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In migrating cells a front-rear polarity is established, with bleb formation restricted to the leading edge, allowing for directed movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In addition to the physical force generated by actin polymerization, microfilaments facilitate the movement of various intracellular components by serving as the roadway along which a family of motor proteins called myosins travel.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin plays a particularly prominent role in muscle cells, which consist largely of repeated bundles of actin and myosin II.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Each repeated unit – called a sarcomere – consists of two sets of oppositely oriented F-actin strands ("thin filaments"), interlaced with bundles of myosin ("thick filaments").
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The two sets of actin strands are oriented with their (+) ends embedded in either end of the sarcomere in delimiting structures called Z-disks.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The myosin fibrils are in the middle between the sets of actin filaments, with strands facing in both directions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] When the muscle contracts, the myosin threads move along the actin filaments towards the (+) end, pulling the ends of the sarcomere together and shortening it by around 70% of its length.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In order to move along the actin thread, myosin must hydrolyze ATP; thus ATP serves as the energy source for muscle contraction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] At times of rest, the proteins tropomyosin and troponin bind to the actin filaments, preventing the attachment of myosin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] When an activation signal (i.e. an action potential) arrives at the muscle fiber, it triggers the release of Ca2+ from the sarcoplasmic reticulum into the cytosol.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The resulting spike in cytosolic calcium rapidly releases tropomyosin and troponin from the actin thread, allowing myosin to bind, and muscle contraction to begin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In the final stages of cell division, many cells form a ring of actin at the cell's midpoint.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This ring, aptly called the "contractile ring", uses a similar mechanism as muscle fibers where myosin II pulls along the actin ring, causing it to contract.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This contraction cleaves the parent cell into two, completing cytokinesis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The contractile ring is composed of actin, myosin, anillin, and α-actinin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In the fission yeast *Schizosaccharomyces pombe*, actin is actively formed in the constricting ring with the participation of Arp3, the formin Cdc12, profilin, and WASp, along with preformed microfilaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Once the ring has been constructed the structure is maintained by a continual assembly and disassembly that, aided by the Arp2/3 complex and formins, is key to one of the central processes of cytokinesis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin-myosin pairs can also participate in the trafficking of various membrane vesicles and organelles within the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Myosin V is activated by binding to various cargo receptors on organelles, and then moves along an actin filament towards the (+) end, pulling its cargo along with it.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These nonconventional myosins use ATP hydrolysis to transport cargo, such as vesicles and organelles, in a directed fashion much faster than diffusion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Myosin V walks towards the barbed end of actin filaments, while myosin VI walks toward the pointed end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Most actin filaments are arranged with the barbed end toward the cellular membrane and the pointed end toward the cellular interior.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This arrangement allows myosin V to be an effective motor for the export of cargos, and myosin VI to be an effective motor for import.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The traditional image of actin's function relates it to the maintenance of the cytoskeleton and, therefore, the organization and movement of organelles, as well as the determination of a cell's shape.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] However, actin has a wider role in eukaryotic cell physiology, in addition to similar functions in prokaryotes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Monomeric actin, or G-actin, has a globular structure consisting of two lobes separated by a deep cleft.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The bottom of the cleft represents the "ATPase fold", a structure conserved among ATP and GTP-binding proteins that binds to a magnesium ion and a molecule of ATP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Binding of ATP or ADP is required to stabilize each actin monomer; without one of these molecules bound, actin quickly becomes denatured.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The X-ray crystallography model of actin that was produced by Kabsch from the striated muscle tissue of rabbits is the most commonly used in structural studies as it was the first to be purified.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The G-actin crystallized by Kabsch is approximately 67 x 40 x 37 Å in size, has a molecular mass of 41,785 Da and an estimated isoelectric point of 4.8.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Elzinga and co-workers first determined the complete peptide sequence for this type of actin in 1973, with later work by the same author adding further detail to the model.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Its N-terminus is highly acidic and starts with an acetyled aspartate in its amino group, while its C-terminus is alkaline and is formed by a phenylalanine preceded by a cysteine, which has a degree of functional importance.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Both extremes are in close proximity within the I-subdomain.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] An anomalous *N*τ-methylhistidine is located at position 73.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The tertiary structure is formed by two domains known as the large and the small, which are separated by a cleft centred around the location of the bond with ATP-ADP+Pi.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Below this there is a deeper notch called a "groove".
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In the native state, despite their names, both have a comparable depth.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The normal convention in topological studies means that a protein is shown with the biggest domain on the left-hand side and the smallest domain on the right-hand side.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In this position the smaller domain is in turn divided into two: subdomain I (lower position, residues 1–32, 70–144, and 338–374) and subdomain II (upper position, residues 33–69).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The larger domain is also divided in two: subdomain III (lower, residues 145–180 and 270–337) and subdomain IV (higher, residues 181–269).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The exposed areas of subdomains I and III are referred to as the "barbed" ends, while the exposed areas of domains II and IV are termed the "pointed" ends.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This nomenclature refers to the fact that, due to the small mass of subdomain II actin is polar; the importance of this will be discussed below in the discussion on assembly dynamics.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Some authors call the subdomains Ia, Ib, IIa, and IIb, respectively.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The most notable supersecondary structure is a five chain beta sheet that is composed of a β-meander and a β-α-β clockwise unit.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It is present in both domains suggesting that the protein arose from gene duplication.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Under various conditions, G-actin molecules polymerize into longer threads called "filamentous-" or "F-actin".
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These F-actin threads are typically composed of two helical strands of actin wound around each other, forming a 7 to 9 nanometer wide helix that repeats every 72 nanometers (or every 14 G-actin subunits).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In F-actin threads, G-actin molecules are all oriented in the same direction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The two ends of the F-actin thread are distinct from one another.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] At one end – designated the (−) end – the ATP-binding cleft of the terminal actin molecule is facing outward.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] At the opposite end – designated (+) – the ATP-binding cleft is buried in the filament, contacting the neighboring actin molecule.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] As F-actin threads grow, new molecules tend to join at the (+) end of an existing F-actin strand.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Conversely, threads tend to shrink by shedding actin monomers from the strand's (−) end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Some proteins, such as cofilin appear to increase the angle of turn, but again this could be interpreted as the establishment of different structural states.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These could be important in the polymerization process.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] There is less agreement regarding measurements of the turn radius and filament thickness: while the first models assigned a length of 25 Å, current X-ray diffraction data, backed up by cryo-electron microscopy suggests a length of 23.7 Å.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These studies have shown the precise contact points between monomers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Some are formed with units of the same chain, between the "barbed" end on one monomer and the "pointed" end of the next one.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] While the monomers in adjacent chains make lateral contact through projections from subdomain IV, with the most important projections being those formed by the C-terminus and the hydrophobic link formed by three bodies involving residues 39–42, 201–203, and 286.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This model suggests that a filament is formed by monomers in a "sheet" formation, in which the subdomains turn about themselves, this form is also found in the bacterial actin homologue MreB.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The terms "pointed" and "barbed" referring to the two ends of the microfilaments derive from their appearance under transmission electron microscopy when samples are examined following a preparation technique called "decoration".
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This method consists of the addition of myosin S1 fragments to tissue that has been fixed with tannic acid.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This myosin forms polar bonds with actin monomers, giving rise to a configuration that looks like arrows with feather fletchings along its shaft, where the shaft is the actin and the fletchings are the myosin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Following this logic, the end of the microfilament that does not have any protruding myosin is called the point of the arrow (− end) and the other end is called the barbed end (+ end).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] A S1 fragment is composed of the head and neck domains of myosin II.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Under physiological conditions, G-actin (the monomer form) is transformed to F-actin (the polymer form) by ATP, where the role of ATP is essential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The helical F-actin filament found in muscles also contains a tropomyosin molecule, which is a 40 nanometre long protein that is wrapped around the F-actin helix.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] During the resting phase the tropomyosin covers the actin's active sites so that the actin-myosin interaction cannot take place and produce muscular contraction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] There are other protein molecules bound to the tropomyosin thread, these are the troponins that have three polymers: troponin I, troponin T, and troponin C.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Unlike other polymers, such as DNA, whose constituent elements are bound together with covalent bonds, the monomers of actin filaments are assembled by weaker bonds.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The lateral bonds with neighbouring monomers resolve this anomaly, which in theory should weaken the structure as they can be broken by thermal agitation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In addition, the weak bonds give the advantage that the filament ends can easily release or incorporate monomers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This means that the filaments can be rapidly remodelled and can change cellular structure in response to an environmental stimulus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Which, along with the biochemical mechanism by which it is brought about is known as the "assembly dynamic".
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin can spontaneously acquire a large part of its tertiary structure.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] However, the way it acquires its fully functional form from its newly synthesized native form is special and almost unique in protein chemistry.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The reason for this special route could be the need to avoid the presence of incorrectly folded actin monomers, which could be toxic as they can act as inefficient polymerization terminators.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Nevertheless, it is key to establishing the stability of the cytoskeleton, and additionally, it is an essential process for coordinating the cell cycle.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] CCT is required in order to ensure that folding takes place correctly.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] CCT is a group II chaperonin, a large protein complex that assists in the folding of other proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] CCT is formed of a double ring of eight different subunits (hetero-octameric) and it differs from group I chaperonins like GroEL, which is found in Eubacteria and in eukaryotic organelles, as it does not require a co-chaperone to act as a lid over the central catalytic cavity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Substrates bind to CCT through specific domains.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It was initially thought that it only bound with actin and tubulin, although recent immunoprecipitation studies have shown that it interacts with a large number of polypeptides, which possibly function as substrates.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It acts through ATP-dependent conformational changes that on occasion require several rounds of liberation and catalysis in order to complete a reaction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In order to successfully complete their folding, both actin and tubulin need to interact with another protein called prefoldin, which is a heterohexameric complex (formed by six distinct subunits), in an interaction that is so specific that the molecules have coevolved.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin forms a complex with prefoldin while it is still being formed, when it is approximately 145 amino acids long, specifically those at the N-terminal.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Different recognition sub-units are used for actin or tubulin although there is some overlap.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In actin the subunits that bind with prefoldin are probably PFD3 and PFD4, which bind in two places one between residues 60–79 and the other between residues 170–198.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The actin is recognized, loaded, and delivered to the cytosolic chaperonin (CCT) in an open conformation by the inner end of prefoldin's "tentacles" (see the image and note).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The contact when actin is delivered is so brief that a tertiary complex is not formed, immediately freeing the prefoldin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The CCT then causes actin's sequential folding by forming bonds with its subunits rather than simply enclosing it in its cavity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This is why it possesses specific recognition areas in its apical β-domain.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The first stage in the folding consists of the recognition of residues 245–249.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Next, other determinants establish contact.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Both actin and tubulin bind to CCT in open conformations in the absence of ATP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In actin's case, two subunits are bound during each conformational change, whereas for tubulin binding takes place with four subunits.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin has specific binding sequences, which interact with the δ and β-CCT subunits or with δ-CCT and ε-CCT.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] After AMP-PNP is bound to CCT the substrates move within the chaperonin's cavity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It also seems that in the case of actin, the CAP protein is required as a possible cofactor in actin's final folding states.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The exact manner by which this process is regulated is still not fully understood, but it is known that the protein PhLP3 (a protein similar to phosducin) inhibits its activity through the formation of a tertiary complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin is an ATPase, which means that it is an enzyme that hydrolyzes ATP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This group of enzymes is characterised by their slow reaction rates.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It is known that this ATPase is "active", that is, its speed increases by some 40,000 times when the actin forms part of a filament.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] A reference value for this rate of hydrolysis under ideal conditions is around 0.3 s−1.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Then, the Pi remains bound to the actin next to the ADP for a long time, until it is cooperatively liberated from the interior of the filament.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The exact molecular details of the catalytic mechanism are still not fully understood.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Although there is much debate on this issue, it seems certain that a "closed" conformation is required for the hydrolysis of ATP, and it is thought that the residues that are involved in the process move to the appropriate distance.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The glutamic acid Glu137 is one of the key residues, which is located in subdomain 1.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Its function is to bind the water molecule that produces a nucleophilic attack on the ATP's γ-phosphate bond, while the nucleotide is strongly bound to subdomains 3 and 4.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The slowness of the catalytic process is due to the large distance and skewed position of the water molecule in relation to the reactant.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] It is highly likely that the conformational change produced by the rotation of the domains between actin's G and F forms moves the Glu137 closer allowing its hydrolysis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] This model suggests that the polymerization and ATPase's function would be decoupled straight away.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The "open" to "closed" transformation between G and F forms and its implications on the relative motion of several key residues and the formation of water wires have been characterized in molecular dynamics and QM/MM simulations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin filaments are often rapidly assembled and disassembled, allowing them to generate force and support cell movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Assembly classically occurs in three steps.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] First, the "nucleation phase", in which two to three G-actin molecules slowly join to form a small oligomer that will nucleate further growth.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Second, the "elongation phase", when the actin filament rapidly grows by the addition of many actin molecules to both ends.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] As the filament grows, actin molecules are added to the (+) end of the filament around 10 times faster than to the (−) end, and so filaments tend to primarily grow at the (+) end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Third, the "steady-state phase", where an equillibrium is reached as actin molecules join and leave the filament at the same rate, maintaining the filament's length.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] While the filament's length remains constant in the steady-state phase, new molecules are constantly being added to the (+) end and falling off the (−) end, a phenomenon called "treadmilling" as a given actin molecule would appear to move along the strand.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In isolation, whether a filament will grow or shrink, and how quickly, are determined by the concentration of G-actin around the filament; however, in cells, the dynamics of actin filaments are heavily influenced by various actin-binding proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The actin cytoskeleton *in vivo* is not exclusively composed of actin, other proteins are required for its formation, continuance, and function.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These proteins are called actin-binding proteins and they are involved in actin's polymerization, depolymerization, stability, and organisation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The diversity of these proteins is such that actin is thought to be the protein that takes part in the greatest number of protein-protein interactions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The nucleation of new actin filaments – the rate-limiting step in actin polymerization – is aided by actin-nucleating proteins such as formins (like formin-2) and the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Formins help to nucleate long actin filaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] They bind two free actin-ATP molecules, bringing them together.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Then as the filament begins to grow, formin moves along the (+) end of the growing filament, all the while recruiting actin-binding proteins that promote filament growth, and excluding capping proteins that would block filament extension.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Branches in actin filaments are typically nucleated by the Arp2/3 complex in concert with nucleation promoting factors.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Nucleation promoting factors bind two free G-actin molecules, then recruit and activate the Arp2/3 complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The activated Arp2/3 complex attaches to an existing actin filament, and uses the two bound G-actin molecules to nucleate a new actin filament branching off of the old one at a 70° angle.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] As filaments grow, the pool of available G-actin molecules is managed by G-actin-binding proteins such as profilin and thymosin β-4.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Profilin ensures a supply of available actin-ATP by binding to ADP-bound G-actin and promoting the exchange of ADP for ATP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Profilin's binding to the actin molecule physically blocks its addition to a filament's (−) end, but permits it to join the (+) end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Once the actin-ATP has joined the filament, profilin releases it.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] As formins promote the nucleation and extension of new actin filaments, they recruit profilin to the area, increasing the local concentration of actin-ATP to boost filament growth.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In contrast, thymosin β-4 binds and sequesters actin-ATP, preventing it from joining a microfilament.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Once an actin fiber is established, the dynamics of its growth or collapse are influenced by numerous proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Existing strands can be interrupted by filament cleaving proteins, such as cofilin and gelsolin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Cofilin binds along two actin-ADP molecules in a filament, forcing a movement that destabilizes the filament and causes it to break.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Gelsolin inserts itself between actin molecules in a filament, disrupting the filament.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] After the filament breaks, gelsolin remains attached to the new (+) end, preventing it from growing, thus forcing its disassembly.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Other proteins bind to the ends of actin filaments, stabilizing them.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These are called "capping proteins" and include CapZ and tropomodulin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] CapZ binds the (+) end of a filament, preventing further addition or loss of actin from that end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Tropomodulin binds to a filament's (−) end, again preventing addition or loss of molecule's at that end.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Tropomodulin is typically found in cells that require extremely stable actin filaments, such as those in muscle and red blood cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] These actin binding proteins are typically regulated by various cellular signals to control actin assembly dynamics in different cellular locations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Formins, for example, are typically folded in an inactive conformation until they're activated by the binding of the small GTPase Rho.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Actin branching at the cell membrane is important for cell movement, and so the plasma membrane lipid PIP2 activates the nucleation promoting factor WASp and inhibits CapZ.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] WASp is also activated by the small GTPase Cdc42, while another nucleation promoting factor WAVE is activated by the GTPase Rac1.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Although most yeasts have only a single actin gene, higher eukaryotes, in general, express several isoforms of actin encoded by a family of related genes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Mammals have at least six actin isoforms coded by separate genes, which are divided into three classes – alpha, beta, and gamma – according to their isoelectric points.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] In general, alpha actins are found in muscle (α-skeletal, α-aortic smooth, α-cardiac), whereas beta and gamma isoforms are prominent in non-muscle cells (β-cytoplasmic, γ1-cytoplasmic, γ2-enteric smooth).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Although the amino acid sequences and *in vitro* properties of the isoforms are highly similar, these isoforms cannot completely substitute for one another *in vivo*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] Plants contains more than 60 actin genes and pseudogenes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The typical actin gene has an approximately 100-nucleotide 5' UTR, a 1200-nucleotide translated region, and a 200-nucleotide 3' UTR.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The majority of actin genes are interrupted by introns, with up to six introns in any of 19 well-characterised locations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p01] The high conservation of the family makes actin the favoured model for studies comparing the introns-early and introns-late models of intron evolution.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Actin and closely related proteins are present in all organisms, suggesting the common ancestor of all life on Earth had actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Actin is one of the most conserved proteins throughout the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The sequences of actin proteins from animals and amoebae are 80% identical despite being separated by approximately one billion years of evolution.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Many unicellular eukaryotes have a single actin gene, while multicellular eukaryotes often have several closely related genes that serve specialized functions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Humans have six; plants have 10 or more.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In addition to actin, eukaryotes have a large family of actin-related proteins, or "Arps", that share a common ancestor with actin and are called Arp1–Arp11, with Arp1 the most closely related to actin, and Arp11 the least.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Bacteria encode three types of actin: MreB influences cell shape, FtsA cell division, and ParM separation of large plasmids.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Some archaea have a bacteria-like MreB gene, while others have an actin gene that more closely resembles eukaryote actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The eukaryotic cytoskeleton of organisms among all taxonomic groups have similar components to actin and tubulin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] For example, the protein that is coded by the *ACTG2* gene in humans is completely equivalent to the homologues present in rats and mice, even though at a nucleotide level the similarity decreases to 92%.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] However, there are major differences with the equivalents in prokaryotes (FtsZ and MreB), where the similarity between nucleotide sequences is between 40 and 50% among different bacteria and archaea species.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Some authors suggest that the ancestral protein that gave rise to the model eukaryotic actin resembles the proteins present in modern bacterial cytoskeletons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Some authors point out that the behaviour of actin, tubulin, and histone, a protein involved in the stabilization and regulation of DNA, are similar in their ability to bind nucleotides and in their ability of take advantage of Brownian motion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It has also been suggested that they all have a common ancestor.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Therefore, evolutionary processes resulted in the diversification of ancestral proteins into the varieties present today, conserving, among others, actins as efficient molecules that were able to tackle essential ancestral biological processes, such as endocytosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The Arp2/3 complex is widely found in all eukaryotic organisms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton contains proteins that are highly similar to actin monomers and polymers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The bacterial protein MreB polymerizes into thin non-helical filaments and occasionally into helical structures similar to F-actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Furthermore, its crystalline structure is very similar to that of G-actin (in terms of its three-dimensional conformation), there are even similarities between the MreB protofilaments and F-actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The bacterial cytoskeleton also contains the FtsZ proteins, which are similar to tubulin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Bacteria therefore possess a cytoskeleton with homologous elements to actin (for example, MreB, AlfA, ParM, FtsA, and MamK), even though the amino acid sequence of these proteins diverges from that present in animal cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] However, such proteins have a high degree of structural similarity to eukaryotic actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The highly dynamic microfilaments formed by the aggregation of MreB and ParM are essential to cell viability and they are involved in cell morphogenesis, chromosome segregation, and cell polarity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] ParM is an actin homologue that is coded in a plasmid and it is involved in the regulation of plasmid DNA.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] ParMs from different bacterial plasmids can form astonishingly diverse helical structures comprising two or four strands to maintain faithful plasmid inheritance.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In archaea the homologue Ta0583 is even more similar to the eukaryotic actins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The majority of mammals possess six different actin genes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Of these, two code for the cytoskeleton (*ACTB* and *ACTG1*) while the other four are involved in skeletal striated muscle (*ACTA1*), smooth muscle tissue (*ACTA2*), intestinal muscles (*ACTG2*) and cardiac muscle (*ACTC1*).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The actin in the cytoskeleton is involved in the pathogenic mechanisms of many infectious agents, including HIV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The vast majority of the mutations that affect actin are point mutations that have a dominant effect, with the exception of six mutations involved in nemaline myopathy.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] This is because in many cases the mutant of the actin monomer acts as a "cap" by preventing the elongation of F-actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The mutation alters the structure and function of skeletal muscles producing one of three forms of myopathy: type 3 nemaline myopathy, congenital myopathy with an excess of thin myofilaments (CM) and congenital myopathy with fibre type disproportion (CMFTD).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Mutations have also been found that produce core myopathies.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Although their phenotypes are similar, in addition to typical nemaline myopathy some specialists distinguish another type of myopathy called actinic nemaline myopathy.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In the former, clumps of actin form instead of the typical rods.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It is important to state that a patient can show more than one of these phenotypes in a biopsy.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The most common symptoms consist of a typical facial morphology (myopathic facies), muscular weakness, a delay in motor development and respiratory difficulties.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The course of the illness, its gravity, and the age at which it appears are all variable and overlapping forms of myopathy are also found.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] A symptom of nemaline myopathy is that "nemaline rods" appear in differing places in type 1 muscle fibres.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] These rods are non-pathognomonic structures that have a similar composition to the Z disks found in the sarcomere.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The pathogenesis of this myopathy is very varied.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Many mutations occur in the region of actin's indentation near to its nucleotide binding sites, while others occur in Domain 2, or in the areas where interaction occurs with associated proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] This goes some way to explain the great variety of clumps that form in these cases, such as Nemaline or Intranuclear Bodies or Zebra Bodies.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Changes in actin's folding occur in nemaline myopathy as well as changes in its aggregation and there are also changes in the expression of other associated proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In some variants where intranuclear bodies are found the changes in the folding masks the nucleus's protein exportation signal so that the accumulation of actin's mutated form occurs in the cell nucleus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that mutations to *ACTA1* that give rise to a CFTDM have a greater effect on sarcomeric function than on its structure.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Recent investigations have tried to understand this apparent paradox, which suggests there is no clear correlation between the number of rods and muscular weakness.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It appears that some mutations are able to induce a greater apoptosis rate in type II muscular fibres.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The *ACTC1* gene codes for the α-actin isoform present in heart muscle.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It was first sequenced by Hamada and co-workers in 1982, when it was found that it is interrupted by five introns.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It was the first of the six genes where alleles were found that were implicated in pathological processes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] A number of structural disorders associated with point mutations of this gene have been described that cause malfunctioning of the heart, such as Type 1R dilated cardiomyopathy and Type 11 hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Certain defects of the atrial septum have been described recently that could also be related to these mutations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Two cases of dilated cardiomyopathy have been studied involving a substitution of highly conserved amino acids belonging to the protein domains that bind and intersperse with the Z discs.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] This has led to the theory that the dilation is produced by a defect in the transmission of contractile force in the myocytes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The mutations in ACTC1 are responsible for at least 5% of hypertrophic cardiomyopathies.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Recent studies have discovered ACTC1 mutations that are implicated in two other pathological processes: Infantile idiopathic restrictive cardiomyopathy, and noncompaction of the left ventricular myocardium.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The *ACTG1* locus codes for the cytosolic γ-actin protein that is responsible for the formation of cytoskeletal microfilaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It contains six exons, giving rise to 22 different mRNAs, which produce four complete isoforms whose form of expression is probably dependent on the type of tissue they are found in.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It also has two different DNA promoters.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It has been noted that the sequences translated from this locus and from that of β-actin are very similar to the predicted ones, suggesting a common ancestral sequence that suffered duplication and genetic conversion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In terms of pathology, it has been associated with processes such as amyloidosis, retinitis pigmentosa, infection mechanisms, kidney diseases, and various types of congenital hearing loss.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Six autosomal-dominant point mutations in the sequence have been found to cause various types of hearing loss, particularly sensorineural hearing loss linked to the DFNA 20/26 locus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It seems that they affect the stereocilia of the ciliated cells present in the inner ear's Organ of Corti. β-actin is the most abundant protein found in human tissue, but it is not very abundant in ciliated cells, which explains the location of the pathology.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] On the other hand, it appears that the majority of these mutations affect the areas involved in linking with other proteins, particularly actomyosin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Some experiments have suggested that the pathological mechanism for this type of hearing loss relates to the F-actin in the mutations being more sensitive to cofilin than normal.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] However, although there is no record of any case, it is known that γ-actin is also expressed in skeletal muscles, and although it is present in small quantities, model organisms have shown that its absence can give rise to myopathies.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Some infectious agents use actin, especially cytoplasmic actin, in their life cycle.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In addition to the previously cited example, actin polymerization is stimulated in the initial steps of the internalization of some viruses, notably HIV, by, for example, inactivating the cofilin complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The role that actin plays in the invasion process of cancer cells has still not been determined.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In conditions of high lipoperoxidation, actin has been shown to be post-translationally modified by the lipoperoxidation product 4-hydroxynonenal (4-HNE).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] This modification prevents the remodelling of the actin cytoskeleton, which is essential for cell motility.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Additionally, another functional protein, coronin-1A, which stabilizes F-actin filaments, is also covalently modified by 4-HNE.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Actin is used in scientific and technological laboratories as a track for molecular motors such as myosin (either in muscle tissue or outside it) and as a necessary component for cellular functioning.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It can also be used as a diagnostic tool, as several of its anomalous variants are related to the appearance of specific pathologies.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The use of actin as an internal control is based on the assumption that its expression is practically constant and independent of experimental conditions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] By comparing the expression of the gene of interest to that of the actin, it is possible to obtain a relative quantity that can be compared between different experiments, whenever the expression of the latter is constant.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] It is worth pointing out that actin does not always have the desired stability in its gene expression.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Actin was first observed experimentally in 1887 by W.D.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Halliburton, who extracted a protein from muscle that 'coagulated' preparations of myosin that he called "myosin-ferment".
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] However, Halliburton was unable to further refine his findings, and the discovery of actin is credited instead to Brunó Ferenc Straub, a young biochemist working in Albert Szent-Györgyi's laboratory at the Institute of Medical Chemistry at the University of Szeged, Hungary.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Following up on the discovery of Ilona Banga & Szent-Györgyi in 1941 that the coagulation only occurs in some myosin extractions and was reversed upon the addition of ATP, Straub identified and purified actin from those myosin preparations that did coagulate.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Building on Banga's original extraction method, he developed a novel technique for extracting muscle protein that allowed him to isolate substantial amounts of relatively pure actin, published in 1942.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Straub's method is essentially the same as that used in laboratories today.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Since Straub's protein was necessary to activate the coagulation of myosin, it was dubbed *actin*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Realizing that Banga's coagulating myosin preparations contained actin as well, Szent-Györgyi called the mixture of both proteins actomyosin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The hostilities of World War II meant Szent-Gyorgyi was unable to publish his lab's work in Western scientific journals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Actin therefore only became well known in the West in 1945, when their paper was published as a supplement to the *Acta Physiologica Scandinavica*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Straub continued to work on actin, and in 1950 reported that actin contains bound ATP and that, during polymerization of the protein into microfilaments, the nucleotide is hydrolyzed to ADP and inorganic phosphate (which remain bound to the microfilament).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Straub suggested that the transformation of ATP-bound actin to ADP-bound actin played a role in muscular contraction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In fact, this is true only in smooth muscle, and was not supported through experimentation until 2001.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The amino acid sequencing of actin was completed by M.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The crystal structure of G-actin was solved in 1990 by Kabsch and colleagues.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In the same year, a model for F-actin was proposed by Holmes and colleagues following experiments using co-crystallization with different proteins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The procedure of co-crystallization with different proteins was used repeatedly during the following years, until in 2001 the isolated protein was crystallized along with ADP.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] However, there is still no high-resolution X-ray structure of F-actin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] The crystallization of G-actin was possible due to the use of a rhodamine conjugate that impedes polymerization by blocking the amino acid cys-374.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Christine Oriol-Audit died in the same year that actin was first crystallized but she was the researcher that in 1977 first crystallized actin in the absence of Actin Binding Proteins (ABPs).
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] However, the resulting crystals were too small for the available technology of the time.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Although no high-resolution model of actin's filamentous form currently exists, in 2008 Sawaya's team were able to produce a more exact model of its structure based on multiple crystals of actin dimers that bind in different places.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] This model has subsequently been further refined by Sawaya and Lorenz.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Other approaches such as the use of cryo-electron microscopy and synchrotron radiation have recently allowed increasing resolution and better understanding of the nature of the interactions and conformational changes implicated in the formation of actin filaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] A number of natural toxins that interfere with actin's dynamics are widely used in research to study actin's role in biology.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Latrunculin – a toxin produced by sponges – binds to G-actin preventing it from joining microfilaments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Cytochalasin D – produced by certain fungi – serves as a capping factor, binding to the (+) end of a filament and preventing further addition of actin molecules.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] In contrast, the sponge toxin jasplakinolide promotes the nucleation of new actin filaments by binding and stabilizing pairs of actin molecules.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Phalloidin – from the "death cap" mushroom *Amanita phalloides* – binds to adjacent actin molecules within the F-actin filament, stabilizing the filament and preventing its depolymerization.
[src:amoeboid-movement/actin-p02] Phalloidin is often labelled with fluorescent dyes to visualize actin filaments by fluorescence microscopy.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] An **action potential** (also known as a **nerve impulse** or "**spike**" when in a neuron) is a series of quick changes in voltage across a cell membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] An action potential occurs when the membrane potential of a specific cell rapidly rises and falls.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This "depolarization" (physically, a reversal of the polarization of the membrane) then causes adjacent locations to similarly depolarize.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Action potentials occur in several types of excitable cells, which include animal cells like neurons and muscle cells, as well as some plant cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Certain endocrine cells such as pancreatic beta cells, and certain cells of the anterior pituitary gland are also excitable cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In other types of cells, their main function is to activate intracellular processes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In muscle cells, for example, an action potential is the first step in the chain of events leading to contraction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In beta cells of the pancreas, they provoke release of insulin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The temporal sequence of action potentials generated by a neuron is called its "spike train".
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A neuron that emits an action potential, or nerve impulse, is often said to "fire".
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are generated by special types of voltage-gated ion channels embedded in a cell's plasma membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These channels are shut when the membrane potential is near the (negative) resting potential of the cell, but they rapidly begin to open if the membrane potential increases to a precisely defined threshold voltage, "depolarising" the membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] When the channels open, they allow an inward flow of sodium ions, which makes the interior of the cell more positive, which further raises the (negative) membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This then causes more channels to open, producing a greater electric current across the cell membrane and so on.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The process proceeds explosively until all of the available ion channels are open, resulting in a large upswing in the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The rapid influx of sodium ions causes the polarity of (i.e. the direction of the electric field across) the plasma membrane to reverse, and the ion channels then rapidly inactivate.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] As the sodium channels close, sodium ions can no longer enter the neuron, and they are then actively transported back out of the plasma membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Potassium channels are then activated, and there is an outward current of potassium ions, returning the electrochemical gradient to the resting state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Because few ions need to pass through to change the potential, the concentrations of ions on either side remain relatively unchanged during this process.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] After an action potential has occurred, there is a transient negative shift, called the afterhyperpolarization.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In animal cells, there are two primary types of action potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] One type is generated by voltage-gated sodium channels, the other by voltage-gated calcium channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Sodium-based action potentials usually last for under one millisecond, but calcium-based action potentials may last for 100 milliseconds or longer.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In some types of neurons, slow calcium spikes provide the driving force for a long burst of rapidly emitted sodium spikes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In cardiac muscle cells, on the other hand, an initial fast sodium spike provides a "primer" to provoke the rapid onset of a calcium spike, which then produces muscle contraction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Nearly all cell membranes in animals, plants and fungi maintain a voltage difference between the exterior and interior of the cell, called the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A typical voltage across an animal cell membrane is −70 mV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This means that the interior of the cell has a negative voltage relative to the exterior.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In most types of cells, the membrane potential usually stays fairly constant.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Some types of cells, however, are electrically active in the sense that their voltages fluctuate over time.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In some types of electrically active cells, including neurons and muscle cells, the voltage fluctuations frequently take the form of a rapid upward (positive) spike followed by a rapid fall.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These up-and-down cycles are known as *action potentials*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Their duration varies considerably with the type of cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In mammalian neurons, the entire up-and-down cycle takes only a few thousandths of a second, while in plant cells, an action potential may last as long as several seconds.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The electrical properties of a cell are determined by the structure of its membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A cell membrane consists of a lipid bilayer of molecules in which larger protein molecules are embedded.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The lipid bilayer is highly resistant to movement of electrically charged ions, so it functions as an insulator.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The large membrane-embedded proteins, in contrast, provide channels through which ions can pass across the membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are driven by channel proteins whose configuration switches between closed and open states as a function of the voltage difference between the interior and exterior of the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These voltage-sensitive proteins are known as voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] All cells in animal body tissues are electrically polarized – in other words, they maintain a voltage difference across the cell's plasma membrane, known as the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This electrical polarization results from a complex interplay between protein structures embedded in the membrane called ion pumps and ion channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In neurons, the types of ion channels in the membrane usually vary across different parts of the cell, giving the dendrites, axon, and cell body different electrical properties.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] As a result, some parts of the membrane of a neuron may be excitable (capable of generating action potentials), whereas others are not.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Recent studies have shown that the most excitable part of a neuron is the part after the axon hillock (the point where the axon leaves the cell body), which is called the axonal initial segment, but the axon and cell body are also excitable in most cases.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Each excitable patch of membrane has two important levels of membrane potential: the resting potential, which is the value the membrane potential maintains as long as nothing perturbs the cell, and a higher value called the threshold potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At the axon hillock of a typical neuron, the resting potential is around −70 millivolts (mV) and the threshold potential is around −55 mV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Synaptic inputs to a neuron cause the membrane to depolarize or hyperpolarize; that is, they cause the membrane potential to rise or fall.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are triggered when enough depolarization accumulates to bring the membrane potential up to threshold.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] When an action potential is triggered, the membrane potential abruptly shoots upward and then equally abruptly shoots back downward, often ending below the resting level, where it remains for some period of time.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The shape of the action potential is stereotyped; this means that the rise and fall usually have approximately the same amplitude and time course for all action potentials in a given cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] (Exceptions are discussed later in the article) In most neurons, the entire process takes place in about a thousandth of a second.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Many types of neurons emit action potentials constantly at rates of up to 10–100 per second.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, some types are much quieter, and may go for minutes or longer without emitting any action potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Action potentials result from the presence in a cell's membrane of special types of voltage-gated ion channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At least one of the conformations creates a channel through the membrane that is permeable to specific types of ions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The transition between conformations is influenced by the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Thus, a voltage-gated ion channel tends to be open for some values of the membrane potential, and closed for others.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In most cases, however, the relationship between membrane potential and channel state is probabilistic and involves a time delay.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Ion channels switch between conformations at unpredictable times: The membrane potential determines the rate of transitions and the probability per unit time of each type of transition.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Voltage-gated ion channels are capable of producing action potentials because they can give rise to positive feedback loops: the membrane potential controls the state of the ion channels, and the state of the ion channels controls the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Thus, in some situations, a rise in the membrane potential can cause ion channels to open, thereby causing a further rise in the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] An action potential occurs when this positive feedback cycle proceeds explosively.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The time and amplitude trajectory of the action potential are determined by the biophysical properties of the voltage-gated ion channels that produce it.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Several types of channels capable of producing the positive feedback necessary to generate an action potential do exist.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Voltage-gated sodium channels are responsible for the fast action potentials involved in nerve conduction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Slower action potentials in muscle cells and some types of neurons are generated by voltage-gated calcium channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Each of these types comes in multiple variants, with different voltage sensitivity and different temporal dynamics.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The most intensively studied type of voltage-dependent ion channels comprises the sodium channels involved in fast nerve conduction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These are sometimes known as Hodgkin-Huxley sodium channels because they were first characterized by Alan Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley in their Nobel Prize-winning studies of the biophysics of the action potential, but can more conveniently be referred to as *Na*V channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] (The "V" stands for "voltage".) An *Na*V channel has three possible states, known as *deactivated*, *activated*, and *inactivated*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The channel is permeable only to sodium ions when it is in the *activated* state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] When the membrane potential is low, the channel spends most of its time in the *deactivated* (closed) state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If the membrane potential is raised above a certain level, the channel shows increased probability of transitioning to the *activated* (open) state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The higher the membrane potential the greater the probability of activation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Once a channel has activated, it will eventually transition to the *inactivated* (closed) state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] It tends then to stay inactivated for some time, but, if the membrane potential becomes low again, the channel will eventually transition back to the *deactivated* state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] During an action potential, most channels of this type go through a cycle *deactivated*→*activated*→*inactivated*→*deactivated*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This is only the population average behavior, however – an individual channel can in principle make any transition at any time.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, the likelihood of a channel's transitioning from the *inactivated* state directly to the *activated* state is very low: A channel in the *inactivated* state is refractory until it has transitioned back to the *deactivated* state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The outcome of all this is that the kinetics of the *Na*V channels are governed by a transition matrix whose rates are voltage-dependent in a complicated way.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Since these channels themselves play a major role in determining the voltage, the global dynamics of the system can be quite difficult to work out.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Hodgkin and Huxley approached the problem by developing a set of differential equations for the parameters that govern the ion channel states, known as the Hodgkin-Huxley equations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These equations have been extensively modified by later research, but form the starting point for most theoretical studies of action potential biophysics.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] As the membrane potential is increased, sodium ion channels open, allowing the entry of sodium ions into the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This is followed by the opening of potassium ion channels that permit the exit of potassium ions from the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The inward flow of sodium ions increases the concentration of positively charged cations in the cell and causes depolarization, where the potential of the cell is higher than the cell's resting potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The sodium channels close at the peak of the action potential, while potassium continues to leave the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The efflux of potassium ions decreases the membrane potential or hyperpolarizes the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] For small voltage increases from rest, the potassium current exceeds the sodium current and the voltage returns to its normal resting value, typically −70 mV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, if the voltage increases past a critical threshold, typically 15 mV higher than the resting value, the sodium current dominates.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This results in a runaway condition whereby the positive feedback from the sodium current activates even more sodium channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Thus, the cell *fires*, producing an action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The frequency at which a neuron elicits action potentials is often referred to as a **firing rate** or **neural firing rate**.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Currents produced by the opening of voltage-gated channels in the course of an action potential are typically significantly larger than the initial stimulating current.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Thus, the amplitude, duration, and shape of the action potential are determined largely by the properties of the excitable membrane and not the amplitude or duration of the stimulus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This all-or-nothing property of the action potential sets it apart from graded potentials such as receptor potentials, electrotonic potentials, subthreshold membrane potential oscillations, and synaptic potentials, which scale with the magnitude of the stimulus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A variety of action potential types exist in many cell types and cell compartments as determined by the types of voltage-gated channels, leak channels, channel distributions, ionic concentrations, membrane capacitance, temperature, and other factors.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The principal ions involved in an action potential are sodium and potassium cations; sodium ions enter the cell, and potassium ions leave, restoring equilibrium.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Relatively few ions need to cross the membrane for the membrane voltage to change drastically.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The ions exchanged during an action potential, therefore, make a negligible change in the interior and exterior ionic concentrations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The few ions that do cross are pumped out again by the continuous action of the sodium–potassium pump, which, with other ion transporters, maintains the normal ratio of ion concentrations across the membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Calcium cations and chloride anions are involved in a few types of action potentials, such as the cardiac action potential and the action potential in the single-cell alga *Acetabularia*, respectively.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Although action potentials are generated locally on patches of excitable membrane, the resulting currents can trigger action potentials on neighboring stretches of membrane, precipitating a domino-like propagation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In contrast to passive spread of electric potentials (electrotonic potential), action potentials are generated anew along excitable stretches of membrane and propagate without decay.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Myelinated sections of axons are not excitable and do not produce action potentials and the signal is propagated passively as electrotonic potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Regularly spaced unmyelinated patches, called the nodes of Ranvier, generate action potentials to boost the signal.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Known as saltatory conduction, this type of signal propagation provides a favorable tradeoff of signal velocity and axon diameter.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Depolarization of axon terminals, in general, triggers the release of neurotransmitter into the synaptic cleft.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In addition, backpropagating action potentials have been recorded in the dendrites of pyramidal neurons, which are ubiquitous in the neocortex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These are thought to have a role in spike-timing-dependent plasticity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In the Hodgkin–Huxley membrane capacitance model, the speed of transmission of an action potential was undefined and it was assumed that adjacent areas became depolarized due to released ion interference with neighbouring channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Measurements of ion diffusion and radii have since shown this not to be possible.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Moreover, contradictory measurements of entropy changes and timing disputed the capacitance model as acting alone.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Alternatively, Gilbert Ling's adsorption hypothesis, posits that the membrane potential and action potential of a living cell is due to the adsorption of mobile ions onto adsorption sites of cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A neuron's ability to generate and propagate an action potential changes during development.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] How much the membrane potential of a neuron changes as the result of a current impulse is a function of the membrane input resistance.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] As a cell grows, more channels are added to the membrane, causing a decrease in input resistance.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A mature neuron also undergoes shorter changes in membrane potential in response to synaptic currents.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Neurons from a ferret lateral geniculate nucleus have a longer time constant and larger voltage deflection at P0 than they do at P30.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] One consequence of the decreasing action potential duration is that the fidelity of the signal can be preserved in response to high frequency stimulation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Immature neurons are more prone to synaptic depression than potentiation after high frequency stimulation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In the early development of many organisms, the action potential is actually initially carried by calcium current rather than sodium current.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The opening and closing kinetics of calcium channels during development are slower than those of the voltage-gated sodium channels that will carry the action potential in the mature neurons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The longer opening times for the calcium channels can lead to action potentials that are considerably slower than those of mature neurons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Xenopus neurons initially have action potentials that take 60–90 ms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] During development, this time decreases to 1 ms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] There are two reasons for this drastic decrease.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] First, the inward current becomes primarily carried by sodium channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Second, the delayed rectifier, a potassium channel current, increases to 3.5 times its initial strength.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In order for the transition from a calcium-dependent action potential to a sodium-dependent action potential to proceed new channels must be added to the membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If Xenopus neurons are grown in an environment with RNA synthesis or protein synthesis inhibitors that transition is prevented.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Even the electrical activity of the cell itself may play a role in channel expression.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If action potentials in Xenopus myocytes are blocked, the typical increase in sodium and potassium current density is prevented or delayed.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This maturation of electrical properties is seen across species.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Xenopus sodium and potassium currents increase drastically after a neuron goes through its final phase of mitosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The sodium current density of rat cortical neurons increases by 600% within the first two postnatal weeks.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Several types of cells support an action potential, such as plant cells, muscle cells, and the specialized cells of the heart (in which occurs the cardiac action potential).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, the main excitable cell is the neuron, which also has the simplest mechanism for the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Neurons are electrically excitable cells composed, in general, of one or more dendrites, a single soma, a single axon and one or more axon terminals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Dendrites are cellular projections whose primary function is to receive synaptic signals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Their protrusions, known as dendritic spines, are designed to capture the neurotransmitters released by the presynaptic neuron.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] They have a high concentration of ligand-gated ion channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These spines have a thin neck connecting a bulbous protrusion to the dendrite.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This ensures that changes occurring inside the spine are less likely to affect the neighboring spines.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The dendritic spine can, with rare exception (see LTP), act as an independent unit.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The dendrites extend from the soma, which houses the nucleus, and many of the "normal" eukaryotic organelles.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Unlike the spines, the surface of the soma is populated by voltage activated ion channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These channels help transmit the signals generated by the dendrites.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Emerging out from the soma is the axon hillock.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This region is characterized by having a very high concentration of voltage-activated sodium channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In general, it is considered to be the spike initiation zone for action potentials, i.e. the trigger zone.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Multiple signals generated at the spines, and transmitted by the soma all converge here.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Immediately after the axon hillock is the axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This is a thin tubular protrusion traveling away from the soma.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The axon is insulated by a myelin sheath.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Myelin is composed of either Schwann cells (in the peripheral nervous system) or oligodendrocytes (in the central nervous system), both of which are types of glial cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Although glial cells are not involved with the transmission of electrical signals, they communicate and provide important biochemical support to neurons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] To be specific, myelin wraps multiple times around the axonal segment, forming a thick fatty layer that prevents ions from entering or escaping the axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This insulation prevents significant signal decay as well as ensuring faster signal speed.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This insulation, however, has the restriction that no channels can be present on the surface of the axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] There are, therefore, regularly spaced patches of membrane, which have no insulation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These nodes of Ranvier can be considered to be "mini axon hillocks", as their purpose is to boost the signal in order to prevent significant signal decay.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At the furthest end, the axon loses its insulation and begins to branch into several axon terminals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These presynaptic terminals, or synaptic boutons, are a specialized area within the axon of the presynaptic cell that contains neurotransmitters enclosed in small membrane-bound spheres called synaptic vesicles.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Before considering the propagation of action potentials along axons and their termination at the synaptic knobs, it is helpful to consider the methods by which action potentials can be initiated at the axon hillock.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The basic requirement is that the membrane voltage at the hillock be raised above the threshold for firing.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] There are several ways in which this depolarization can occur.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Action potentials are most commonly initiated by excitatory postsynaptic potentials from a presynaptic neuron.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Typically, neurotransmitter molecules are released by the presynaptic neuron.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These neurotransmitters then bind to receptors on the postsynaptic cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This binding opens various types of ion channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This opening has the further effect of changing the local permeability of the cell membrane and, thus, the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If the binding increases the voltage (depolarizes the membrane), the synapse is excitatory.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If, however, the binding decreases the voltage (hyperpolarizes the membrane), it is inhibitory.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Whether the voltage is increased or decreased, the change propagates passively to nearby regions of the membrane (as described by the cable equation and its refinements).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Typically, the voltage stimulus decays exponentially with the distance from the synapse and with time from the binding of the neurotransmitter.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Some fraction of an excitatory voltage may reach the axon hillock and may (in rare cases) depolarize the membrane enough to provoke a new action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] More typically, the excitatory potentials from several synapses must work together at nearly the same time to provoke a new action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Their joint efforts can be thwarted, however, by the counteracting inhibitory postsynaptic potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Neurotransmission can also occur through electrical synapses.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Due to the direct connection between excitable cells in the form of gap junctions, an action potential can be transmitted directly from one cell to the next in either direction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The free flow of ions between cells enables rapid non-chemical-mediated transmission.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Rectifying channels ensure that action potentials move only in one direction through an electrical synapse.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Electrical synapses are found in all nervous systems, including the human brain, although they are a distinct minority.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The amplitude of an action potential is often thought to be independent of the amount of current that produced it.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In other words, larger currents do not create larger action potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Therefore, action potentials are said to be all-or-none signals, since either they occur fully or they do not occur at all.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This is in contrast to receptor potentials, whose amplitudes are dependent on the intensity of a stimulus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In both cases, the frequency of action potentials is correlated with the intensity of a stimulus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In sensory neurons, an external signal such as pressure, temperature, light, or sound is coupled with the opening and closing of ion channels, which in turn alter the ionic permeabilities of the membrane and its voltage.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These voltage changes can again be excitatory (depolarizing) or inhibitory (hyperpolarizing) and, in some sensory neurons, their combined effects can depolarize the axon hillock enough to provoke action potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Some examples in humans include the olfactory receptor neuron and Meissner's corpuscle, which are critical for the sense of smell and touch, respectively.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, not all sensory neurons convert their external signals into action potentials; some do not even have an axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Instead, they may convert the signal into the release of a neurotransmitter, or into continuous graded potentials, either of which may stimulate subsequent neuron(s) into firing an action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] For illustration, in the human ear, hair cells convert the incoming sound into the opening and closing of mechanically gated ion channels, which may cause neurotransmitter molecules to be released.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In sensory neurons, action potentials result from an external stimulus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, some excitable cells require no such stimulus to fire: They spontaneously depolarize their axon hillock and fire action potentials at a regular rate, like an internal clock.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The voltage traces of such cells are known as pacemaker potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The cardiac pacemaker cells of the sinoatrial node in the heart provide a good example.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Although such pacemaker potentials have a natural rhythm, it can be adjusted by external stimuli; for instance, heart rate can be altered by pharmaceuticals as well as signals from the sympathetic and parasympathetic nerves.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The external stimuli do not cause the cell's repetitive firing, but merely alter its timing.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In some cases, the regulation of frequency can be more complex, leading to patterns of action potentials, such as bursting.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The course of the action potential can be divided into five parts: the rising phase, the peak phase, the falling phase, the undershoot phase, and the refractory period.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] During the rising phase the membrane potential depolarizes (becomes more positive).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The point at which depolarization stops is called the peak phase.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At this stage, the membrane potential reaches a maximum.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Subsequent to this, there is a falling phase.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] During this stage the membrane potential becomes more negative, returning towards resting potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The undershoot, or afterhyperpolarization, phase is the period during which the membrane potential temporarily becomes more negatively charged than when at rest (hyperpolarized).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Finally, the time during which a subsequent action potential is impossible or difficult to fire is called the refractory period, which may overlap with the other phases.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The course of the action potential is determined by two coupled effects.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] First, voltage-sensitive ion channels open and close in response to changes in the membrane voltage *Vm*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This changes the membrane's permeability to those ions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Second, according to the Goldman equation, this change in permeability changes the equilibrium potential *Em*, and, thus, the membrane voltage *Vm*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Thus, the membrane potential affects the permeability, which then further affects the membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This sets up the possibility for positive feedback, which is a key part of the rising phase of the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A complicating factor is that a single ion channel may have multiple internal "gates" that respond to changes in *Vm* in opposite ways, or at different rates.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] For example, although raising *Vm* *opens* most gates in the voltage-sensitive sodium channel, it also *closes* the channel's "inactivation gate", albeit more slowly.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Hence, when *Vm* is raised suddenly, the sodium channels open initially, but then close due to the slower inactivation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The voltages and currents of the action potential in all of its phases were modeled accurately by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Huxley in 1952, for which they were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1963.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, their model considers only two types of voltage-sensitive ion channels, and makes several assumptions about them, e.g., that their internal gates open and close independently of one another.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In reality, there are many types of ion channels, and they do not always open and close independently.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A typical action potential begins at the axon hillock with a sufficiently strong depolarization, e.g., a stimulus that increases *Vm*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This depolarization is often caused by the injection of extra sodium cations into the cell; these cations can come from a wide variety of sources, such as chemical synapses, sensory neurons or pacemaker potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] For a neuron at rest, there is a high concentration of sodium and chloride ions in the extracellular fluid compared to the intracellular fluid, while there is a high concentration of potassium ions in the intracellular fluid compared to the extracellular fluid.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The difference in concentrations, which causes ions to move from a high to a low concentration, and electrostatic effects (attraction of opposite charges) are responsible for the movement of ions in and out of the neuron.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The inside of a neuron has a negative charge, relative to the cell exterior, from the movement of K+ out of the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The neuron membrane is more permeable to K+ than to other ions, allowing this ion to selectively move out of the cell, down its concentration gradient.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This concentration gradient along with potassium leak channels present on the membrane of the neuron causes an efflux of potassium ions making the resting potential close to *E*K ≈ −75 mV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Since Na+ ions are in higher concentrations outside of the cell, the concentration and voltage differences both drive them into the cell when Na+ channels open.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Depolarization opens both the sodium and potassium channels in the membrane, allowing the ions to flow into and out of the axon, respectively.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If the depolarization is small (say, increasing *Vm* from −70 mV to −60 mV), the outward potassium current overwhelms the inward sodium current and the membrane repolarizes back to its normal resting potential around −70 mV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, if the depolarization is large enough, the inward sodium current increases more than the outward potassium current and a runaway condition (positive feedback) results: the more inward current there is, the more *Vm* increases, which in turn further increases the inward current.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A sufficiently strong depolarization (increase in *Vm*) causes the voltage-sensitive sodium channels to open; the increasing permeability to sodium drives *Vm* closer to the sodium equilibrium voltage *E*Na≈ +55 mV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The increasing voltage in turn causes even more sodium channels to open, which pushes *Vm* still further towards *E*Na.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This positive feedback continues until the sodium channels are fully open and *Vm* is close to *E*Na.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The sharp rise in *Vm* and sodium permeability correspond to the *rising phase* of the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The critical threshold voltage for this runaway condition is usually around −45 mV, but it depends on the recent activity of the axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] A cell that has just fired an action potential cannot fire another one immediately, since the Na+ channels have not recovered from the inactivated state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The period during which no new action potential can be fired is called the *absolute refractory period*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At longer times, after some but not all of the ion channels have recovered, the axon can be stimulated to produce another action potential, but with a higher threshold, requiring a much stronger depolarization, e.g., to −30 mV.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The period during which action potentials are unusually difficult to evoke is called the *relative refractory period*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The positive feedback of the rising phase slows and comes to a halt as the sodium ion channels become maximally open.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At the peak of the action potential, the sodium permeability is maximized and the membrane voltage *Vm* is nearly equal to the sodium equilibrium voltage *E*Na.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, the same raised voltage that opened the sodium channels initially also slowly shuts them off, by closing their pores; the sodium channels become *inactivated*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This lowers the membrane's permeability to sodium relative to potassium, driving the membrane voltage back towards the resting value.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At the same time, the raised voltage opens voltage-sensitive potassium channels; the increase in the membrane's potassium permeability drives *Vm* towards *E*K.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Combined, these changes in sodium and potassium permeability cause *Vm* to drop quickly, repolarizing the membrane and producing the "falling phase" of the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The depolarized voltage opens additional voltage-dependent potassium channels, and some of these do not close right away when the membrane returns to its normal resting voltage.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In addition, further potassium channels open in response to the influx of calcium ions during the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The intracellular concentration of potassium ions is transiently unusually low, making the membrane voltage *Vm* even closer to the potassium equilibrium voltage *E*K.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The membrane potential goes below the resting membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Hence, there is an undershoot or hyperpolarization, termed an afterhyperpolarization, that persists until the membrane potassium permeability returns to its usual value, restoring the membrane potential to the resting state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Each action potential is followed by a refractory period, which can be divided into an *absolute refractory period*, during which it is impossible to evoke another action potential, and then a *relative refractory period*, during which a stronger-than-usual stimulus is required.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These two refractory periods are caused by changes in the state of sodium and potassium channel molecules.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] When closing after an action potential, sodium channels enter an "inactivated" state, in which they cannot be made to open regardless of the membrane potential—this gives rise to the absolute refractory period.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Even after a sufficient number of sodium channels have transitioned back to their resting state, it frequently happens that a fraction of potassium channels remains open, making it difficult for the membrane potential to depolarize, and thereby giving rise to the relative refractory period.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Because the density and subtypes of potassium channels may differ greatly between different types of neurons, the duration of the relative refractory period is highly variable.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The absolute refractory period is largely responsible for the unidirectional propagation of action potentials along axons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At any given moment, the patch of axon behind the actively spiking part is refractory, but the patch in front, not having been activated recently, is capable of being stimulated by the depolarization from the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The action potential generated at the axon hillock propagates as a wave along the axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The currents flowing inwards at a point on the axon during an action potential spread out along the axon, and depolarize the adjacent sections of its membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If sufficiently strong, this depolarization provokes a similar action potential at the neighboring membrane patches.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This basic mechanism was demonstrated by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin in 1937.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] After crushing or cooling nerve segments and thus blocking the action potentials, he showed that an action potential arriving on one side of the block could provoke another action potential on the other, provided that the blocked segment was sufficiently short.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Once an action potential has occurred at a patch of membrane, the membrane patch needs time to recover before it can fire again.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] At the molecular level, this *absolute refractory period* corresponds to the time required for the voltage-activated sodium channels to recover from inactivation, i.e., to return to their closed state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] There are many types of voltage-activated potassium channels in neurons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] On the other hand, all neuronal voltage-activated sodium channels inactivate within several milliseconds during strong depolarization, thus making following depolarization impossible until a substantial fraction of sodium channels have returned to their closed state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Although it limits the frequency of firing, the absolute refractory period ensures that the action potential moves in only one direction along an axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The currents flowing in due to an action potential spread out in both directions along the axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, only the unfired part of the axon can respond with an action potential; the part that has just fired is unresponsive until the action potential is safely out of range and cannot restimulate that part.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In the usual orthodromic conduction, the action potential propagates from the axon hillock towards the synaptic knobs (the axonal termini); propagation in the opposite direction—known as antidromic conduction—is very rare.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, if a laboratory axon is stimulated in its middle, both halves of the axon are "fresh", i.e., unfired; then two action potentials will be generated, one traveling towards the axon hillock and the other traveling towards the synaptic knobs.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] To enable fast and efficient transduction of electrical signals in the nervous system, certain neuronal axons are covered with myelin sheaths.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Myelin is a multilamellar membrane that enwraps the axon in segments separated by intervals known as nodes of Ranvier.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] It is produced by specialized cells: Schwann cells exclusively in the peripheral nervous system, and oligodendrocytes exclusively in the central nervous system.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Myelin sheath reduces membrane capacitance and increases membrane resistance in the inter-node intervals, thus allowing a fast, saltatory movement of action potentials from node to node.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Myelination is found mainly in vertebrates, but an analogous system has been discovered in a few invertebrates, such as some species of shrimp.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Not all neurons in vertebrates are myelinated; for example, axons of the neurons comprising the autonomic nervous system are not, in general, myelinated.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Myelin prevents ions from entering or leaving the axon along myelinated segments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] As a general rule, myelination increases the conduction velocity of action potentials and makes them more energy-efficient.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Whether saltatory or not, the mean conduction velocity of an action potential ranges from 1 meter per second (m/s) to over 100 m/s, and, in general, increases with axonal diameter.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Action potentials cannot propagate through the membrane in myelinated segments of the axon.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, the current is carried by the cytoplasm, which is sufficient to depolarize the first or second subsequent node of Ranvier.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Instead, the ionic current from an action potential at one node of Ranvier provokes another action potential at the next node; this apparent "hopping" of the action potential from node to node is known as saltatory conduction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Although the mechanism of saltatory conduction was suggested in 1925 by Ralph Lillie, the first experimental evidence for saltatory conduction came from Ichiji Tasaki and Taiji Takeuchi and from Andrew Huxley and Robert Stämpfli.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] By contrast, in unmyelinated axons, the action potential provokes another in the membrane immediately adjacent, and moves continuously down the axon like a wave.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Myelin has two important advantages: fast conduction speed and energy efficiency.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] For axons larger than a minimum diameter (roughly 1 micrometre), myelination increases the conduction velocity of an action potential, typically tenfold.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Conversely, for a given conduction velocity, myelinated fibers are smaller than their unmyelinated counterparts.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] For example, action potentials move at roughly the same speed (25 m/s) in a myelinated frog axon and an unmyelinated squid giant axon, but the frog axon has a roughly 30-fold smaller diameter and 1000-fold smaller cross-sectional area.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Also, since the ionic currents are confined to the nodes of Ranvier, far fewer ions "leak" across the membrane, saving metabolic energy.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] This saving is a significant selective advantage, since the human nervous system uses approximately 20% of the body's metabolic energy.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The length of axons' myelinated segments is important to the success of saltatory conduction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] They should be as long as possible to maximize the speed of conduction, but not so long that the arriving signal is too weak to provoke an action potential at the next node of Ranvier.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In nature, myelinated segments are generally long enough for the passively propagated signal to travel for at least two nodes while retaining enough amplitude to fire an action potential at the second or third node.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Thus, the safety factor of saltatory conduction is high, allowing transmission to bypass nodes in case of injury.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] However, action potentials may end prematurely in certain places where the safety factor is low, even in unmyelinated neurons; a common example is the branch point of an axon, where it divides into two axons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Some diseases degrade myelin and impair saltatory conduction, reducing the conduction velocity of action potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The most well-known of these is multiple sclerosis, in which the breakdown of myelin impairs coordinated movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] The flow of currents within an axon can be described quantitatively by cable theory and its elaborations, such as the compartmental model.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Cable theory was developed in 1855 by Lord Kelvin to model the transatlantic telegraph cable and was shown to be relevant to neurons by Hodgkin and Rushton in 1946.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In simple cable theory, the neuron is treated as an electrically passive, perfectly cylindrical transmission cable, which can be described by a partial differential equation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] where *V*(*x*, *t*) is the voltage across the membrane at a time *t* and a position *x* along the length of the neuron, and where λ and τ are the characteristic length and time scales on which those voltages decay in response to a stimulus.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] Referring to the circuit diagram on the right, these scales can be determined from the resistances and capacitances per unit length.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] These time and length-scales can be used to understand the dependence of the conduction velocity on the diameter of the neuron in unmyelinated fibers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] For example, the time-scale τ increases with both the membrane resistance *rm* and capacitance *cm*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] As the capacitance increases, more charge must be transferred to produce a given transmembrane voltage (by the equation *Q* = *CV*); as the resistance increases, less charge is transferred per unit time, making the equilibration slower.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] In a similar manner, if the internal resistance per unit length *ri* is lower in one axon than in another (e.g., because the radius of the former is larger), the spatial decay length λ becomes longer and the conduction velocity of an action potential should increase.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p01] If the transmembrane resistance *rm* is increased, that lowers the average "leakage" current across the membrane, likewise causing *λ* to become longer, increasing the conduction velocity.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] In general, action potentials that reach the synaptic knobs cause a neurotransmitter to be released into the synaptic cleft.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Neurotransmitters are small molecules that may open ion channels in the postsynaptic cell; most axons have the same neurotransmitter at all of their termini.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The arrival of the action potential opens voltage-sensitive calcium channels in the presynaptic membrane; the influx of calcium causes vesicles filled with neurotransmitter to migrate to the cell's surface and release their contents into the synaptic cleft.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This complex process is inhibited by the neurotoxins tetanospasmin and botulinum toxin, which are responsible for tetanus and botulism, respectively.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Some synapses dispense with the "middleman" of the neurotransmitter, and connect the presynaptic and postsynaptic cells together.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] When an action potential reaches such a synapse, the ionic currents flowing into the presynaptic cell can cross the barrier of the two cell membranes and enter the postsynaptic cell through pores known as connexons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Thus, the ionic currents of the presynaptic action potential can directly stimulate the postsynaptic cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Electrical synapses allow for faster transmission because they do not require the slow diffusion of neurotransmitters across the synaptic cleft.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Hence, electrical synapses are used whenever fast response and coordination of timing are crucial, as in escape reflexes, the retina of vertebrates, and the heart.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] A special case of a chemical synapse is the neuromuscular junction, in which the axon of a motor neuron terminates on a muscle fiber.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] In such cases, the released neurotransmitter is acetylcholine, which binds to the acetylcholine receptor, an integral membrane protein in the membrane (the *sarcolemma*) of the muscle fiber.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] However, the acetylcholine does not remain bound; rather, it dissociates and is hydrolyzed by the enzyme, acetylcholinesterase, located in the synapse.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This enzyme quickly reduces the stimulus to the muscle, which allows the degree and timing of muscular contraction to be regulated delicately.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Some poisons inactivate acetylcholinesterase to prevent this control, such as the nerve agents sarin and tabun, and the insecticides diazinon and malathion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The cardiac action potential differs from the neuronal action potential by having an extended plateau, in which the membrane is held at a high voltage for a few hundred milliseconds prior to being repolarized by the potassium current as usual.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This plateau is due to the action of slower calcium channels opening and holding the membrane voltage near their equilibrium potential even after the sodium channels have inactivated.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The cardiac action potential plays an important role in coordinating the contraction of the heart.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The cardiac cells of the sinoatrial node provide the pacemaker potential that synchronizes the heart.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The action potentials of those cells propagate to and through the atrioventricular node (AV node), which is normally the only conduction pathway between the atria and the ventricles.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Action potentials from the AV node travel through the bundle of His and thence to the Purkinje fibers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Conversely, anomalies in the cardiac action potential—whether due to a congenital mutation or injury—can lead to human pathologies, especially arrhythmias.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Several anti-arrhythmia drugs act on the cardiac action potential, such as quinidine, lidocaine, beta blockers, and verapamil.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The action potential in a normal skeletal muscle cell is similar to the action potential in neurons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Action potentials result from the depolarization of the cell membrane (the sarcolemma), which opens voltage-sensitive sodium channels; these become inactivated and the membrane is repolarized through the outward current of potassium ions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The resting potential prior to the action potential is typically −90mV, somewhat more negative than typical neurons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The muscle action potential lasts roughly 2–4 ms, the absolute refractory period is roughly 1–3 ms, and the conduction velocity along the muscle is roughly 5 m/s.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The action potential releases calcium ions that free up the tropomyosin and allow the muscle to contract.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Muscle action potentials are provoked by the arrival of a pre-synaptic neuronal action potential at the neuromuscular junction, which is a common target for neurotoxins.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Plant and fungal cells are also electrically excitable.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The fundamental difference from animal action potentials is that the depolarization in plant cells is not accomplished by an uptake of positive sodium ions, but by release of negative *chloride* ions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Bose published the first measurements of action potentials in plants, which had previously been discovered by Burdon-Sanderson and Darwin.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] An increase in cytoplasmic calcium ions may be the cause of anion release into the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This makes calcium a precursor to ion movements, such as the influx of negative chloride ions and efflux of positive potassium ions, as seen in barley leaves.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The initial influx of calcium ions also poses a small cellular depolarization, causing the voltage-gated ion channels to open and allowing full depolarization to be propagated by chloride ions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] *Dionaea muscipula*) use sodium-gated channels to operate plant movements and "count" stimulation events to determine if a threshold for movement is met.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] *Dionaea muscipula*, also known as the Venus flytrap, is found in subtropical wetlands in North and South Carolina.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] When there are poor soil nutrients, the flytrap relies on a diet of insects and animals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Despite research on the plant, there lacks an understanding behind the molecular basis to the Venus flytraps, and carnivore plants in general.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] However, plenty of research has been done on action potentials and how they affect movement and clockwork within the Venus flytrap.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] To start, the resting membrane potential of the Venus flytrap (−120 mV) is lower than animal cells (usually −90 mV to −40 mV).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The lower resting potential makes it easier to activate an action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Thus, when an insect lands on the trap of the plant, it triggers a hair-like mechanoreceptor.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This receptor then activates an action potential that lasts around 1.5 ms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This causes an increase of positive calcium ions into the cell, slightly depolarizing it.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] However, the flytrap does not close after one trigger.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Instead, it requires the activation of two or more hairs.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] If only one hair is triggered, it disregards the activation as a false positive.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Further, the second hair must be activated within a certain time interval (0.75–40 s) for it to register with the first activation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Thus, a buildup of calcium begins and then slowly falls after the first trigger.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] When the second action potential is fired within the time interval, it reaches the calcium threshold to depolarize the cell, closing the trap on the prey within a fraction of a second.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Together with the subsequent release of positive potassium ions the action potential in plants involves an osmotic loss of salt (KCl).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Whereas, the animal action potential is osmotically neutral because equal amounts of entering sodium and leaving potassium cancel each other osmotically.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The interaction of electrical and osmotic relations in plant cells appears to have arisen from an osmotic function of electrical excitability in a common unicellular ancestors of plants and animals under changing salinity conditions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Further, the present function of rapid signal transmission is seen as a newer accomplishment of metazoan cells in a more stable osmotic environment.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] It is likely that the familiar signaling function of action potentials in some vascular plants (e.g.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] *Mimosa pudica*) arose independently from that in metazoan excitable cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Unlike the rising phase and peak, the falling phase and after-hyperpolarization seem to depend primarily on cations that are not calcium.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] To initiate repolarization, the cell requires movement of potassium out of the cell through passive transportation on the membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This differs from neurons because the movement of potassium does not dominate the decrease in membrane potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] To fully repolarize, a plant cell requires energy in the form of ATP to assist in the release of hydrogen from the cell – utilizing a transporter called proton ATPase.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Action potentials are found throughout multicellular organisms, including plants, invertebrates such as insects, and vertebrates such as reptiles and mammals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Sponges seem to be the main phylum of multicellular eukaryotes that does not transmit action potentials, although some studies have suggested that these organisms have a form of electrical signaling, too.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The resting potential, as well as the size and duration of the action potential, have not varied much with evolution, although the conduction velocity does vary dramatically with axonal diameter and myelination.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Given its conservation throughout evolution, the action potential seems to confer evolutionary advantages.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] One function of action potentials is rapid, long-range signaling within the organism; the conduction velocity can exceed 110 m/s, which is one-third the speed of sound.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] For comparison, a hormone molecule carried in the bloodstream moves at roughly 8 m/s in large arteries.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Part of this function is the tight coordination of mechanical events, such as the contraction of the heart.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] A second function is the computation associated with its generation.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Being an all-or-none signal that does not decay with transmission distance, the action potential has similar advantages to digital electronics.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The integration of various dendritic signals at the axon hillock and its thresholding to form a complex train of action potentials is another form of computation, one that has been exploited biologically to form central pattern generators and mimicked in artificial neural networks.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The common prokaryotic/eukaryotic ancestor, which lived perhaps four billion years ago, is believed to have had voltage-gated channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] This functionality was likely, at some later point, cross-purposed to provide a communication mechanism.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Even modern single-celled bacteria can utilize action potentials to communicate with other bacteria in the same biofilm.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The study of action potentials has required the development of new experimental methods.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The initial work, prior to 1955, was carried out primarily by Alan Lloyd Hodgkin and Andrew Fielding Huxley, who were, along John Carew Eccles, awarded the 1963 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for their contribution to the description of the ionic basis of nerve conduction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] It focused on three goals: isolating signals from single neurons or axons, developing fast, sensitive electronics, and shrinking electrodes enough that the voltage inside a single cell could be recorded.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The first problem was solved by studying the giant axons found in the neurons of the squid (*Loligo forbesii* and *Doryteuthis pealeii*, at the time classified as *Loligo pealeii*).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] These axons are so large in diameter (roughly 1 mm, or 100-fold larger than a typical neuron) that they can be seen with the naked eye, making them easy to extract and manipulate.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] However, they are not representative of all excitable cells, and numerous other systems with action potentials have been studied.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Since the current equals *C* times the rate of change of the transmembrane voltage *Vm*, the solution was to design a circuit that kept *Vm* fixed (zero rate of change) regardless of the currents flowing across the membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Thus, the current required to keep *Vm* at a fixed value is a direct reflection of the current flowing through the membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Other electronic advances included the use of Faraday cages and electronics with high input impedance, so that the measurement itself did not affect the voltage being measured.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The third problem, that of obtaining electrodes small enough to record voltages within a single axon without perturbing it, was solved in 1949 with the invention of the glass micropipette electrode, which was quickly adopted by other researchers.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Refinements of this method are able to produce electrode tips that are as fine as 100 Å (10 nm), which also confers high input impedance.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Action potentials may also be recorded with small metal electrodes placed just next to a neuron, with neurochips containing EOSFETs, or optically with dyes that are sensitive to Ca2+ or to voltage.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] While glass micropipette electrodes measure the sum of the currents passing through many ion channels, studying the electrical properties of a single ion channel became possible in the 1970s with the development of the patch clamp by Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] For this discovery, they were awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine in 1991.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Patch-clamping verified that ionic channels have discrete states of conductance, such as open, closed and inactivated.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Optical imaging technologies have been developed in recent years to measure action potentials, either via simultaneous multisite recordings or with ultra-spatial resolution.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Using voltage-sensitive dyes, action potentials have been optically recorded from a tiny patch of cardiomyocyte membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Several neurotoxins, both natural and synthetic, function by blocking the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Tetrodotoxin from the pufferfish and saxitoxin from the *Gonyaulax* (the dinoflagellate genus responsible for "red tides") block action potentials by inhibiting the voltage-sensitive sodium channel; similarly, dendrotoxin from the black mamba snake inhibits the voltage-sensitive potassium channel.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Such inhibitors of ion channels serve an important research purpose, by allowing scientists to "turn off" specific channels at will, thus isolating the other channels' contributions; they can also be useful in purifying ion channels by affinity chromatography or in assaying their concentration.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] However, such inhibitors also make effective neurotoxins, and have been considered for use as chemical weapons.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Neurotoxins aimed at the ion channels of insects have been effective insecticides; one example is the synthetic permethrin, which prolongs the activation of the sodium channels involved in action potentials.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The ion channels of insects are sufficiently different from their human counterparts that there are few side effects in humans.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The role of electricity in the nervous systems of animals was first observed in dissected frogs by Luigi Galvani, who studied it from 1791 to 1797.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Galvani's results inspired Alessandro Volta to develop the Voltaic pile—the earliest-known electric battery—with which he studied animal electricity (such as electric eels) and the physiological responses to applied direct-current voltages.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] In the 19th century scientists studied the propagation of electrical signals in whole nerves (i.e., bundles of neurons) and demonstrated that nervous tissue was made up of cells, instead of an interconnected network of tubes (a *reticulum*).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Carlo Matteucci followed up Galvani's studies and demonstrated that injured nerves and muscles in frogs could produce direct current.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Matteucci's work inspired the German physiologist, Emil du Bois-Reymond, who discovered in 1843 that stimulating these muscle and nerve preparations produced a notable diminution in their resting currents, making him the first researcher to identify the electrical nature of the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The conduction velocity of action potentials was then measured in 1850 by du Bois-Reymond's friend, Hermann von Helmholtz.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Progress in electrophysiology stagnated thereafter due to the limitations of chemical theory and experimental practice.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] To establish that nervous tissue is made up of discrete cells, the Spanish physician Santiago Ramón y Cajal and his students used a stain developed by Camillo Golgi to reveal the myriad shapes of neurons, which they rendered painstakingly.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] For their discoveries, Golgi and Ramón y Cajal were awarded the 1906 Nobel Prize in Physiology.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Their work resolved a long-standing controversy in the neuroanatomy of the 19th century; Golgi himself had argued for the network model of the nervous system.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The 20th century saw significant breakthroughs in electrophysiology.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] In 1902 and again in 1912, Julius Bernstein advanced the hypothesis that the action potential resulted from a change in the permeability of the axonal membrane to ions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Bernstein's hypothesis was confirmed by Ken Cole and Howard Curtis, who showed that membrane conductance increases during an action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] In 1907, Louis Lapicque suggested that the action potential was generated as a threshold was crossed, what would be later shown as a product of the dynamical systems of ionic conductances.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] In 1949, Alan Hodgkin and Bernard Katz refined Bernstein's hypothesis by considering that the axonal membrane might have different permeabilities to different ions; in particular, they demonstrated the crucial role of the sodium permeability for the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] They made the first actual recording of the electrical changes across the neuronal membrane that mediate the action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Hodgkin and Huxley correlated the properties of their mathematical model with discrete ion channels that could exist in several different states, including "open", "closed", and "inactivated".
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Their hypotheses were confirmed in the mid-1970s and 1980s by Erwin Neher and Bert Sakmann, who developed the technique of patch clamping to examine the conductance states of individual ion channels.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] In the 21st century, researchers are beginning to understand the structural basis for these conductance states and for the selectivity of channels for their species of ion, through the atomic-resolution crystal structures, fluorescence distance measurements and cryo-electron microscopy studies.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Julius Bernstein was also the first to introduce the Nernst equation for resting potential across the membrane; this was generalized by David E.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Goldman to the eponymous Goldman equation in 1943.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The sodium–potassium pump was identified in 1957 and its properties gradually elucidated, culminating in the determination of its atomic-resolution structure by X-ray crystallography.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The crystal structures of related ionic pumps have also been solved, giving a broader view of how these molecular machines work.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] Mathematical and computational models are essential for understanding the action potential, and offer predictions that may be tested against experimental data, providing a stringent test of a theory.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The most important and accurate of the early neural models is the Hodgkin–Huxley model, which describes the action potential by a coupled set of four ordinary differential equations (ODEs).
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] The properties of the Hodgkin–Huxley and FitzHugh–Nagumo models and their relatives, such as the Bonhoeffer–Van der Pol model, have been well-studied within mathematics, computation and electronics.
[src:amoeboid-movement/action-potential-p02] However the simple models of generator potential and action potential fail to accurately reproduce the near threshold neural spike rate and spike shape, specifically for the mechanoreceptors like the Pacinian corpuscle.
[src:amoeboid-movement/active-matter] Research in active matter combines analytical techniques, numerical simulations and experiments.
[src:amoeboid-movement/active-matter] Notable analytical approaches include hydrodynamics, kinetic theory, and non-equilibrium statistical physics.
[src:amoeboid-movement/active-matter] Numerical studies mainly involve self-propelled-particles models, making use of agent-based models such as molecular dynamics algorithms or lattice-gas models, as well as computational studies of hydrodynamic equations of active fluids.
[src:amoeboid-movement/active-matter] Experiments on synthetic systems include self-propelled colloids (e.g., phoretically propelled particles), driven granular matter (e.g. vibrated monolayers), swarming robots, and Quincke rotators.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] The discovery of aerotaxis was first reported by Theodor Wilhelm Engelmann, as he showed microaerophilic *Spirillum tenue* were attracted by low oxygen concentrations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] Ten decades after the first discovery of this movement, it was observed that bacteria are actually bound to areas with optimal oxygen concentrations; resulting in the formation of bands.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] It was concluded that the creations of these bands was largely in part to oxygen's important role in metabolic pathways as they allowed for surveying aerotaxis in many bacterial species.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] This ability proves to be important for survival as efficient metabolism directly relates to growth.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] Aerotaxis not only describes the response to energy source, but also the signal transductions across organisms to create ecosystems.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] As growing conditions change, such as the availability of oxygen, bacteria capable of energy taxis travel towards nutrient concentrations which are metabolically beneficial.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] The direction of travel is determined utilizing a transducer, such as Aer or Tsr proteins in *E. coli*, which detect changes in either electron transport or proton motive force.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] Aerotaxis, similar to other types of bacterial taxis, involves repeated cycles of straight-line swimming followed by short reversals that reorient bacteria so that they are constantly drawn up their oxygen gradients toward attractants and away from repellants.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] Aerotaxis is a dominant sensory system and will cause organisms to follow their oxygen gradient even if it makes them move against other chemical gradients.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] Using *Shewanella oneidensis*, a Gram-negative facultative aerobic bacteria, as their model organism, a group of scientists looked to visualize the aerotactic bands formed by aerotactic bacteria.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] This bacterial strain is considered pivotal for sustainable technologies because of its ability to shift electrons from an electron donor towards an electron acceptor available in the environment like solid metals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] By trapping an air bubble in-between a microscope slide and cover slip with the use of a spacer, the team was able to watch how the bacteria migrated to the air pocket over time.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] After about 20 minutes the bacteria started to aggregate around the air bubble and form a distinct band.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] The bacteria move in-between the bubble and the ring, and as time passes and air is used up, the ring shrinks towards the bubble.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] Phase-contrast microscopy reveals a layer of bacteria piled up at the air–liquid interface and surrounded by a depletion zone after the air bubble has been used up.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] In the closed set up air supply is limited and used up so a layer of bacteria is unable to build.
[src:amoeboid-movement/aerotaxis] However, in an open set up with an unlimited air supply, a notable layer of bacteria continue to build at the air-liquid interface.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] An **amoeba** or **ameba** /əˈmiːbə/ (pl.: **amoebas** or **amebas** (less commonly, **amoebae** or **amebae** /əˈmiːbi/)), often called an **amoeboid**, is a type of cell or unicellular organism with the ability to alter its shape, primarily by extending and retracting pseudopods.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebae do not form a single taxonomic group; instead, they are found in every major lineage of eukaryotic organisms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoeboid cells occur not only among the protozoa, but also in fungi, algae, and animals.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Microbiologists often use the terms "amoeboid" and "amoeba" interchangeably for any organism that exhibits amoeboid movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] In older classification systems, most amoebae were placed in the class or subphylum Sarcodina, a grouping of single-celled organisms that possess pseudopods or move by protoplasmic flow.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] However, molecular phylogenetic studies have shown that Sarcodina is not a monophyletic group whose members share common descent.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Consequently, amoeboid organisms are no longer classified together in one group.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The best known amoeboid protists are *Chaos carolinense* and *Amoeba proteus*, both of which have been widely cultivated and studied in classrooms and laboratories.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Other well known species include the so-called "brain-eating amoeba" *Naegleria fowleri*, the intestinal parasite *Entamoeba histolytica*, which causes amoebic dysentery, and the multicellular "social amoeba" or slime mould *Dictyostelium discoideum*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebae do not have cell walls, which allows for free movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebae move and feed by using pseudopods, which are bulges of cytoplasm formed by the coordinated action of actin microfilaments pushing out the plasma membrane that surrounds the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The appearance and internal structure of pseudopods are used to distinguish groups of amoebae from one another.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebozoan species, such as those in the genus *Amoeba*, typically have bulbous (lobose) pseudopods, rounded at the ends and roughly tubular in cross-section.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Cercozoan amoeboids, such as *Euglypha* and *Gromia*, have slender, thread-like (filose) pseudopods.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Foraminifera emit fine, branching pseudopods that merge with one another to form net-like (reticulose) structures.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Some groups, such as the Radiolaria and Heliozoa, have stiff, needle-like, radiating axopodia (actinopoda) supported from within by bundles of microtubules.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Free-living amoebae may be "testate" (enclosed within a hard shell), or "naked" (also known as gymnamoebae, lacking any hard covering).
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The shells of testate amoebae may be composed of various substances, including calcium, silica, chitin, or agglutinations of found materials like small grains of sand and the frustules of diatoms.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] To regulate osmotic pressure, most freshwater amoebae have a contractile vacuole which expels excess water from the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] This organelle is necessary because freshwater has a lower concentration of solutes (such as salt) than the amoeba's own internal fluids (cytosol).
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Because the surrounding water is hypotonic with respect to the contents of the cell, water is transferred across the amoeba's cell membrane by osmosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Without a contractile vacuole, the cell would fill with excess water and, eventually, burst.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Marine amoebae do not usually possess a contractile vacuole because the concentration of solutes within the cell are in balance with the tonicity of the surrounding water.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Some amoebae are predatory and live by consuming bacteria and other protists.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Some are detritivores and eat dead organic material.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebae typically ingest their food by phagocytosis, extending pseudopods to encircle and engulf live prey or particles of scavenged material.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoeboid cells do not have a mouth or cytostome, and there is no fixed place on the cell at which phagocytosis normally occurs.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Some amoebae also feed by pinocytosis, imbibing dissolved nutrients through vesicles formed within the cell membrane.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The size of amoeboid cells and species is extremely variable.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The marine amoeboid *Massisteria voersi* is just 2.3 to 3 micrometres in diameter, within the size range of many bacteria.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] At the other extreme, the shells of deep-sea xenophyophores can attain 20 cm in diameter.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Most of the free-living freshwater amoebae commonly found in pond water, ditches, and lakes are microscopic, but some species, such as the so-called "giant amoebae" *Pelomyxa palustris* and *Chaos carolinense*, can be large enough to see with the naked eye.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Recent evidence indicates that several Amoebozoa lineages undergo meiosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Orthologs of genes employed in meiosis of sexual eukaryotes have recently been identified in the *Acanthamoeba* genome.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] This finding suggests that the ''Acanthamoeba'' are capable of some form of meiosis and may be able to undergo sexual reproduction.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The meiosis-specific recombinase, Dmc1, is required for efficient meiotic homologous recombination, and *Dmc1* is expressed in *Entamoeba histolytica*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The purified Dmc1 from *E. histolytica* forms presynaptic filaments and catalyses ATP-dependent homologous DNA pairing and DNA strand exchange over at least several thousand base pairs.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The DNA pairing and strand exchange reactions are enhanced by the eukaryotic meiosis-specific recombination accessory factor (heterodimer) Hop2-Mnd1.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] These processes are central to meiotic recombination, suggesting that *E. histolytica* undergoes meiosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Studies of *Entamoeba invadens* found that, during the conversion from the tetraploid uninucleate trophozoite to the tetranucleate cyst, homologous recombination is enhanced.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Expression of genes with functions related to the major steps of meiotic recombination also increase during encystations.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] These findings in *E. invadens*, combined with evidence from studies of *E. histolytica* indicate the presence of meiosis in the *Entamoeba*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Since the Amoebozoa diverged early from the eukaryotic family tree, these results suggest that meiosis was present early in eukaryotic evolution.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Furthermore, these findings are consistent with the proposal of Lahr et al. that the majority of amoeboid lineages are anciently sexual.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebae have been found to harvest and grow the bacteria implicated in plague.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebae can likewise play host to microscopic organisms that are pathogenic to people and help in spreading such microbes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Bacterial pathogens (for example, *Legionella*) can oppose absorption of food when devoured by amoebae.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The currently generally utilized and best-explored amoebae that host other organisms are Acanthamoeba castellanii and Dictyostelium discoideum.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Microorganisms that can overcome the defenses of one-celled organisms can shelter and multiply inside them, where they are shielded from unfriendly outside conditions by their hosts.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The earliest record of an amoeboid organism was produced in 1755 by August Johann Rösel von Rosenhof, who named his discovery "Der Kleine Proteus" ("the Little Proteus").
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Rösel's illustrations show an unidentifiable freshwater amoeba, similar in appearance to the common species now known as *Amoeba proteus*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The term "Proteus animalcule" remained in use throughout the 18th and 19th centuries, as an informal name for any large, free-living amoeboid.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] In 1822, the genus *Amiba* (from the Greek ἀμοιβή *amoibe*, meaning "change") was erected by the French naturalist Bory de Saint-Vincent.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Ehrenberg, adopted the genus in his own classification of microscopic creatures, but changed the spelling to *Amoeba*.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] In 1841, Félix Dujardin coined the term "*sarcode*" (from Greek σάρξ *sarx*, "flesh", and εἶδος *eidos*, "form") for the "thick, glutinous, homogeneous substance" which fills protozoan cell bodies.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Although the term originally referred to the protoplasm of any protozoan, it soon came to be used in a restricted sense to designate the gelatinous contents of amoeboid cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Thirty years later, the Austrian zoologist Ludwig Karl Schmarda used "sarcode" as the conceptual basis for his division Sarcodea, a phylum-level group made up of "unstable, changeable" organisms with bodies largely composed of "sarcode".
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Later workers, including the influential taxonomist Otto Bütschli, amended this group to create the class Sarcodina, a taxon that remained in wide use throughout most of the 20th century.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] For convenience, all amoebae were grouped as Sarcodina and generally divided into morphological categories, on the basis of the form and structure of their pseudopods.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoebae with pseudopods supported by regular arrays of microtubules (such as the freshwater Heliozoa and marine Radiolaria) were classified as **Actinopoda**, whereas those with unsupported pseudopods were classified as **Rhizopoda**.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The Rhizopods were further subdivided into lobose, filose, plasmodial and reticulose, according to the morphology of their pseudopods.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] In the final decades of the 20th century, a series of molecular phylogenetic analyses confirmed that Sarcodina was not a monophyletic group, and that amoebae evolved from flagellate ancestors.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] In his scheme, the Sarcodina were divided into the more primitive **Eosarcodina** (with the phyla Reticulosa and Mycetozoa) and the more derived **Neosarcodina** (with the phyla Amoebozoa for lobose amoebae and Rhizopoda for filose amoebae).
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Shortly after, phylogenetic analyses disproved this hypothesis, as non-amoeboid zooflagellates and amoeboflagellates were found to be completely intermingled with amoebae.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] With the addition of many flagellates to Rhizopoda and the removal of some amoebae, the name was rejected in favour of a new name Cercozoa.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] As such, both names Rhizopoda and Sarcodina were finally abandoned as formal taxa, but they remained useful as descriptive terms for amoebae.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The phylum Amoebozoa was conserved, as it still primarily included amoeboid organisms, and now included the Mycetozoa.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Today, amoebae are dispersed among many high-level taxonomic groups.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The majority of traditional sarcodines are placed in two eukaryote supergroups: Amoebozoa and Rhizaria.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The rest have been distributed among the excavates, opisthokonts, stramenopiles and minor clades.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Some multicellular organisms have amoeboid cells only in certain phases of life, or use amoeboid movements for specialized functions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] In the immune system of humans and other animals, amoeboid white blood cells pursue invading organisms, such as bacteria and pathogenic protists, and engulf them by phagocytosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Sponges exhibit a totipotent cell type known as archaeocytes, capable of transforming into the feeding cells or choanocytes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Amoeboid stages also occur in the multicellular fungus-like protists, the so-called slime moulds.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Both the plasmodial slime moulds, currently classified in the class Myxogastria, and the cellular slime moulds of the groups Acrasida and Dictyosteliida, live as amoebae during their feeding stage.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] The amoeboid cells of the former combine to form a giant multinucleate organism, while the cells of the latter live separately until food runs out, at which time the amoebae aggregate to form a multicellular migrating "slug" which functions as a single organism.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeba] Other organisms may also present amoeboid cells during certain life-cycle stages, e.g., the gametes of some green algae (Zygnematophyceae) and pennate diatoms, the spores (or dispersal phases) of some Mesomycetozoea, and the sporoplasm stage of Myxozoa and of Ascetosporea.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Movement occurs when the cytoplasm slides and forms a pseudopodium in front to pull the cell forward.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Some examples of organisms that exhibit this type of locomotion are amoebae (such as *Amoeba proteus* and *Naegleria gruberi*,) and slime molds, as well as some cells in humans such as leukocytes.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Sarcomas, or cancers arising from connective tissue cells, are particularly adept at amoeboid movement, thus leading to their high rate of metastasis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] This type of movement has been linked to changes in action potential.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] While several hypotheses have been proposed to explain the mechanism of amoeboid movement, its exact mechanisms are not yet well understood.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Assembly and disassembly of actin filaments in cells may be important to the biochemical and biophysical mechanisms that contribute to different types of cellular movements in both striated muscle structures and nonmuscle cells.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Polarity gives cells distinct leading and lagging edges through the shifting of proteins selectively to the poles, and may play an important role in eukaryotic chemotaxis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Crawling is one form of amoeboid movement which starts when an extension of the moving cell (pseudopod) binds tightly to the surface.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] The main bulk of the cell pulls itself toward the bound patch.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] By repeating this process the cell can move until the first bound patch is at the very end of the cell, at which point it detaches.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] The speed at which cells crawl can vary greatly, but generally crawling is faster than swimming, but slower than gliding on a smooth surface.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] However, crawling does not become notably slower on uneven and irregular surfaces, while gliding becomes much slower under such conditions.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] It seems that crawling can be either bleb-driven or actin-driven (see sections below), depending on the nature of the surface.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Gliding is similar to crawling, but is characterized by much less adhesion to the surface, making it faster on smoother surfaces which require less traction but slower on more difficult and complicated surfaces.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Some cells glide with the same mechanism as crawling, but with larger pseudopods and less surface adhesion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Other cells use a different method to glide: a small patch of the cell already touching the surface binds to the surface, after which the cytoskeleton pushes or pulls on the anchored patch to slide the cell forward.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] This differs from the aforementioned mechanism in that the cell does not extend a pseudopod, so there is relatively little deformation of the cell as it progresses.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Many different prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells can swim and many of these have either flagella or cilia for that purpose.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] These dedicated structures are not necessary for swimming, though, as there are amoeba and other eukaryotic cells which lack flagella and cilia but can still swim, although it is slower than crawling or gliding.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] There are two different proposed mechanisms for amoeboid swimming.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] In the first the cell extends small pseudopods which then move down the sides of the cell, acting like paddles.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] In the second the cell generates an internal flow cycle, with the cytoplasm flowing backward along the membrane edge and forward through the middle, generating a force on the membrane which moves the cell forward.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] The protoplasm of an amoeba is made up of an outer layer termed the ectoplasm which surrounds an inner portion called the endoplasm.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] The ectoplasm consists of a gelatinous semisolid called plasma gel whereas the endoplasm is made up of a less viscous fluid called plasma sol.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] The ectoplasm owes its highly viscous state, in part, to the cross-linking actomyosin complex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Locomotion of an amoeba is thought to occur due to the sol-gel conversion of the protoplasm within its cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] For example, when an amoeba moves, it extends a gelatinous, cytosolic pseudopodium, which then results in the more fluid cytosol (plasma sol) flowing after the gelatinous portion (plasma gel) where it congeals at the end of the pseudopodium.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] This results in the extension of this appendage.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] On the opposite (posterior) end of the cell, plasma gel is then converted to plasma sol and streamed toward the advancing pseudopodium.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] As long as the cell has a way to grapple the substratum, repetition of this process guides the cell forward.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Inside the amoeba, there are proteins that can be activated to convert the gel into the more liquid sol state.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Cytoplasm consist largely of actin and actin is regulated by actin-binding protein.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Actin binding proteins are in turn regulated by calcium ions; hence, calcium ions are very important in the sol-gel conversion process.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Based on some mathematical models, recent studies hypothesize a novel biological model for collective biomechanical and molecular mechanisms of cellular motion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] It is proposed that microdomains weave the texture of cytoskeleton and their interactions mark the location for formation of new adhesion sites.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] According to this model, microdomain signaling dynamics organize the cytoskeleton and its interaction with the substratum.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] As microdomains trigger and maintain active polymerization of actin filaments, their propagation and zigzagging motion on the membrane generate a highly interlinked network of curved or linear filaments oriented at a wide spectrum of angles to the cell boundary.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] It has also been proposed that microdomain interaction marks the formation of new focal adhesion sites at the cell periphery.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] The interaction of myosin with the actin network then generates membrane retraction/ruffling, retrograde flow, and contractile forces for forward motion.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Finally, continuous application of stress on the old focal adhesion sites could result in the calcium-induced activation of calpain, and consequently the detachment of focal adhesions which completes the cycle.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] In addition to actin polymerization, microtubules may also play an important role in cell migration where the formation of lamellipodia is involved.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] One experiment showed that although microtubules are not required for actin polymerization to create lamellipodial extensions, they are needed in order to afford cellular movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Another such proposed mechanism, the 'bleb-driven amoeboid locomotion' mechanism, suggests that the cell cortex actomyosin contracts to increase hydrostatic pressure inside the cell.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Blebbing occurs in amoeboid cells when there is a roughly spherical protrusion in the cell membrane characterized by detachment from the actomyosin cortex.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] This mode of amoeboid movement requires that myosin II play a role in generating the hydrostatic pressure that causes the bleb to extend.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] This is different from actin-driven locomotion where the protrusion created is by the actin polymerizing while remaining attached to the actomyosin cortex and physically pushing against the cell's barrier.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] During the bleb-driven amoeboid movement, the cytoplasmic sol-gel state is regulated.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Blebbing can also be a sign of when a cell is undergoing apoptosis.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] It has also been observed that the blebs formed by motile cells undergo a roughly uniform life cycle that lasts approximately one minute.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] This includes a phase involving the initial outward expansion where the membrane breaks away from the membranous cytoskeleton.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] This is then followed by a short static phase where the hydrostatic pressure that has built up is just enough to maintain the size of the bleb.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Following this is the last phase characterized by the bleb slowly retracting and the membrane being reintroduced to the cytoskeleton infrastructure.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Cells may undergo fast transitions between blebbing and lamellipodium-based motility as a means of migration.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] However, the rate at which these transitions are made is still unknown.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Tumor cells may also exhibit rapid transitions between amoeboid motility and mesenchymal motility, another form of cellular movement.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Dictyostelium cells and neutrophils can also swim, using a similar mechanism as for crawling.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] Another unicellular form of movement shown in Euglena is known as metaboly.
[src:amoeboid-movement/amoeboid-movement] The basis of sol gel theory is interconversion of sol and gel.
